<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solana Briefs German Leaders on NATO-Russia Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
said here today that the security pact reached between the western
military alliance and Russia two days ago was approved by NATO
countries today and will be made public within days after the
verification of different language versions of the text.
</P>
<P>
Solana is in Bonn today to brief German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
and Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel on details of the new security
pact between NATO and Russia, announced by himself and Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov in Moscow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after his talks with Kinkel,
Solana said it was a "historic agreement in which everybody is a
winner, and nobody is a loser". He stressed that the accord would
bring more security, more stability and the possibility for more
prosperity in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the document, to be signed by NATO
countries and Russia on May 27 in Paris, will not be legally
binding, and thus will not require ratification by parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Council, NATO's governing body, approved the
document in Brussels this morning. The pact defines relations,
cooperation and security between NATO and Russia in view of the
planned expansion of the alliance to take in former Soviet bloc
countries in central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia has strongly opposed NATO expansion, insisting that it
will create new gulfs in Europe and threaten its security. Russia
wanted NATO to guarantee that it would not station nuclear
weapons or military forces on the territory of new members and
would not use military facilities left over by the former Warsaw
Pact Organization in those countries.
</P>
<P>
Solana said today NATO had already made a statement in December
last year which said it had "no reason, no plan and no intention"
to station nuclear weapons in new member states. That statement
had been incorporated in the new document, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement doesn't go into detail about military facilities,
Solana said. But NATO will be able to utilize the infrastructure
needed to undertake missions for "collective defence" and for
peace-keeping, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's basic security concerns would be taken care of by a
joint consultation mechanism to be created between NATO and Russia
where the two sides "will construct a close, deep, and profound
relationship," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
Both Solana and Kinkel stopped short of saying which countries
will be invited to join NATO in the first wave. Solana said the
decision had not yet been made but would without doubt be made
during the NATO summit on July 8-9 in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the Czech Republic, Hungary, and
Poland will be the first candidates.
</P>
<P>
Solana said a declaration defining relations between NATO and
Ukraine would also be formally signed at the NATO summit in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
