<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Implement "One Country-Two Systems" After Hong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 16 (Xinhua) -- China will implement the "one
country-two systems" policy after Hong Kong's reversion so as to
maintain the region's stability and prosperity, a senior Chinese
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The "one country-two systems" policy, initiated by late Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping, is not an interim policy, its is a
solidly-established and long-standing policy of China, Lu Ping,
director of China's Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office, told an
international conference on Asia's future.
</P>
<P>
China wants to preserve Hong Kong's economy as it provides
great benefits to China's modernization and opening to the
outside. The best way to achieve this is to implement the policy,
lu said.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) will retain its present economic and social systems for at
least the next 50 years. The Hong Kong SAR will still implement
the systems and policies of capitalism and retain a high of
autonomy in all areas except for defense and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official also expressed his belief that Hong Kong's
future government, under the leadership of Tung Chee-hwa, will do
its utmost to maintain Hong Kong's stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew also addressed the
conference, predicting that business in Hong Kong will be as
usual after its handover.
</P>
<P>
Lee, former Singapore prime minister, said he was confident of
Hong Kong's post-1997 future because its economy is in
exceptionally good shape, with local and international confidence
in it as a high level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
