<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Construction Up 2.6 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The housing starts in the U.S.
increased by 2.6 percent in April resulting from the fastest pace
of apartment building in seven years, the U.S. Commerce Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the housing starts rose to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.47 million units following a sharp 7.7
percent drop in March and a 13 percent jump in February.
</P>
<P>
Single-family construction inched only 0.3 percent higher last
month to 1.12 million units. Builders began construction of
two-to-four-unit buildings at an annual rate of 41,000, up 2.5
percent. But the starts of apartment buildings reached to the
highest level since January 1990.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. housing starts in the first four months of this
year declined by a modest 3.5 percent comparing with the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, housing starts in the South were up by 11.3 percent
in the month, the largest increase in the country and the highest
in the region since July 1995. Starts edged 0.7 percent higher in
the Midwest following a 24.9 percent drop in March. But housing
starts fell by 7.4 percent in the Northeast and 6.5 percent in the
West.
</P>
<P>
In a signal of future activity, applications for housing
permits fell by 0.8 percent in April to an annual rate of 1.45
million units. Permits for multi-unit construction, from two units
up, dropped by 9.7 percent to a rate of 382,000 units. Those for
single-family rose 2.9 percent to a rate of 1.06 million units.
</P>
</TEXT>
