<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Departure of Mobutu Opened Way for Peaceful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said on Friday that the departure of President
Mobutu Sese Seko opened the way for peaceful resolution of the
conflict in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kinshasa said Mobutu left the Zairian capital for
his northern palace and a spokesman for the government said at a
press conference that the president "ceased all intervention in
the affairs of the state."
</P>
<P>
The Zairian government statement indicated that Mobutu
apparently ended his 32-year rule of the central African country,
observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Before her talks with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy,
Albright told reporters: "We believe that his departure now opens
the way for a peaceful resolution of the military conflict."
</P>
<P>
"We are at this stage working with all the parties so that we
can avoid bloodshed and also to do what can be done in terms of
contributing to a process that would be peaceful and have an
inclusive transition that would result in free and fair
elections," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I think the most important point here is that Zaire now needs
to move forward away from war towards peace, stability and
elections," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
