<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumers Urged To Keep Duty-Free In EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide consumer awareness
campaign was launched here today by the Duty-Free Confederation
(DFC), as part of the fight to prevent the abolition of duty and
tax-free shopping in the EU in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
In its initial phase, three million leaflets will be
distributed to consumers at airport shops, on airlines and ferries
and in ticket wallets over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
The leaflets have a freepost tear-off slip which consumers can
send back to the Duty-Free Confederation for further information
on how they can help.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are encouraged to write to their local MP and MEP
telling them their views and make the point that everybody
benefits from duty-free.
</P>
<P>
A Duty-Freephone hotline has also been set up to provide
consumers with information on how they will be affected by the
abolition and give them assistance with how they can help.
</P>
<P>
It is claimed that up to 33,000 jobs in the European ferry
industry and tourism could be lost and half of the ferry services
serving Britain and Ireland could be withdrawn if the European
Union abolishes duty-free sales.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the campaign is to persuade European governments
to authorize a further extension of cross-border duty-free
privileges originally planned to end when the single European
market was created in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
"Duty free is not just a valuable perk for the holiday
motorist, it is an integral part of the funding of sea and air
travel," said Barry Goddard, Secretary General of the DFC.
</P>
<P>
"Ultimately it is the consumers who will bear the cost of the
abolition of duty and tax-free shopping, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
