<HEADLINE> S.Leone Rebels' Attacks Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Parliament of Sierra Leone on
Thursday passed without dissent a private member's motion
condemning the resumption of attacks by the rebel Revolutionary
United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
The motion also called on the government ''to take prompt
action'' to protect life and property and ''to legalise civil
defence units'' in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to independent sources, there are about three main
civil defence units in the country, established mainly on a
regional basis, the most prominent being the Kamajors and the
Kapras.
</P>
<P>
Legislators also called for the setting up of a war council
but no decision was made on the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
A total of 30 people died during RUF attack on Bomaru in the
east of the country last Monday.
</P>
<P>
A member of parliament on Wednesday told the legislature about
the attack but gave no casualty figure.
</P>
<P>
Travellers arriving in the capital said 23 civilians died and
28 others were wounded and now admitted at a hospital in
Segbwema.
</P>
<P>
''The condition of most of the wounded are very serious as they
were butchered with blunt machetes and other crude weapons,'' one
Sierra Leone Red Cross official said.
</P>
<P>
One Red Cross official reported seeing a letter left behind
by the attackers saying, ''we have jumped on the rampage again. we
are not going to ceasefire until our leader Foday Sankoh is
released from detention (in Nigeria).''
</P>
<P>
A doctor at the Segbwema hospital reached by telephone,
Emerson Musa said the casualties ''are the largest caseload I
have ever handled since the war.'' He has sent an urgent
message to medical officials in Freetown ''for food, blood and
rugs which are now on the way.''
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said the rebels who attacked Bomaru were about
100. enditem




