<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Fails to Meet EU Beef Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Reduced slaughter stock and the
madcow disease scare last year resulted in a lower tonnage of
beef exports to the European Union market by the Zimbabwe's
state-owned Cold Storage Company (CSC), an official said today.
</P>
<P>
CSC Public Relations Manager Joyce Sibanda said that the
parastatal only managed to export 6,600 tonnes of beef worth 23.6
million US dollars, falling short of its annual quota of 9,100
tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Sibanda said, ''CSC's performance in 1996 was affected by a
number of factors, namely low throughput due to the reduced
slaughter stock in the country, and the BSE (madcow disease)
scare in Europe which led to a drop in consumption and price
levels, and temporary suspension of exports into the United
Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
She said the export market this year would depend on
throughput as the national herd had still not recovered to the
pre-drought levels.
</P>
<P>
She added the CSC would, however, want the government to
renegotiate the Africa, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) Protocol and
ask the EU to increase its beef quota in the year 2000. enditem

