<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Support Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said today it is ready to support Zimbabwe's economic
reform program once the southern African country finalises the
blue print for the second phase of the reforms.
</P>
<P>
IMF Deputy Managing Director Alassane Ouattara said in Harare
support would resume as soon as the Zimbabwe government has put
in place a satisfactory policy package to ensure success of the
second phase of reforms scheduled to start this year.
</P>
<P>
He said while there were signs of positive growth over the
past year, there was still need to consolidate the gains realised
so far by putting in place prudent economic policies that could
sustain the growth.
</P>
<P>
He added, ''this country has great potential and to achieve
this, the country needs not only increased support from local
institutions but also the international community.''
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended disbursement of 91 million US dollars in
1995 after accusing Zimbabwe of missing agreed economic targets
under the first phase of reforms.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and other donors want Zimbabwe to cut its budget
deficit to at least five percent of GDP, although this is proving
to be an elusive goal, as admitted this week by Zimbabwean
Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa who said the deficit would shoot
to 11.4 percent of GDP by the year ending June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ouattara, who arrived in the country on Thursday, and
President Robert Mugabe discussed earlier the economic situation
in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He was expected to leave Zimbabwe for Tanzania on Saturday.
enditem

