<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobutu Leaves Kinshasa to "Stay in Background" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko
left Kinshasa today for his fief Gbadolite in northern Zaire, in
order to "stay in the background," said the Zairian government
today.
</P>
<P>
"In order not to appear as an obstacle to a negotiated
solution and the constitutional order, the president has decided
to stay in the background," the Zairian council of ministers
(cabinet) said in a communique.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has not announced the resignation of
Mobutu, who has ruled Zaire for 32 years.
</P>
<P>
A diplomatic source in Rabat, Morocco, said that Mobutu asked
on Thursday the right to make a stopover of his plane in Rabat in
the coming few days. King Hassan II of Morocco is a close friend
of Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States State Department said that the
Zairian rebel forces led by Laurent-Desire Kabila are continuing
their advance toward Kinshasa, and are now 35 to 50 kilometers
from the capital.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Secretary of State Madelaine Albright said that the
departure of Mobutu "has opened the way to a peaceful solution of
the military conflict" and said that Washington is keeping
contact with both sides of the Zairian conflict to avoid "flow of
blood."
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse quoted a source of Zairian rebels as
saying that some advanced units of the rebels are near the
international airport of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry said today that it does not have
any information on a possible arrival of Mobutu in France, where
the president owns a luxury villa near the southern Mediterranean
city of Nice.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss government today froze Mobutu's properties in
Switzerland, including a villa 40 kilometers south of Lausanne, at
the demand of the Zairian rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
