<HEADLINE> Smuggled Clothing Threatens Zimbabwe's Textile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's largest textile company
today warned the industry's futute is under serious threat from
smuggled goods.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of David Whitehead Textiles Ltd Chris Parvin said unless
regional governments tightened border controls, the domestic market
share of textile and clothing companies would continue to be eroded
by cheap imports, particularly from the Far East.
</P>
<P>
''The regional market, including South Africa, is plagued with the
same problems facing Zimbabwean textile manufacturers, particularly
smuggled and under-invoiced goods,'' Parvin said in a statement
accompanying the company's half-year results for the period to March
1997.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''We understand that in South Africa, the Customs
department are recruiting additional inspectors to try and contain
these illegal imports.''
</P>
<P>
''If these goods find their way into the regional markets, further
damage to textile and clothing companies will result,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He denied that local textile and clothing companies were not
competitive as alleged by some critics, saying their problems were to
a large extent caused by unfair competition, as well as the
government's excessive expenditure, which resulted in high inflation
and interest rates. enditem

