<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Atlantic Council Approves NATO-Russian Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Council today
gave its approval to a deal reached between NATO and Russia on
mutual relations, cooperation and security, it was learned here
today.
</P>
<P>
The Founding Act on Mutual Relations, Cooperation and Security
was negotiated by NATO Secretary General Javier Solana and Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov in Moscow on Tuesday and
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The act will be formally signed by Mr. Solana and heads of
state and government of NATO and Russia in Paris on May 27, 1997,
according to a press release issued by NATO here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Russia has agreed to allow NATO to expand
towards the borders of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
It was the climax of months of diplomacy aimed at calming the
long-time Russian apprehensions about NATO enlargement, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
The deal has cleared the way for the May 27 signing ceremony in
Paris and the expected invitations in July to the Czech Republic,
Hungary and Poland to become NATO members, analysts also said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
