<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Urged to Use PTA  Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert
Murerwa has challenged the country's entrepreneurs to utilise
facilities offered by the PTA Bank amid concern by indigenous
business people that they are shunned by existing financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa, who was recently elected chairman of the Board of
Governors of the Eastern and Southern African Trade and Development
Bank (PTA Bank), today said despite being one of the largest
shareholders in the regional bank, Zimbabwe had not submitted
projects last year for funding under the bank's project finance
scheme.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''the board has therefore agreed to set up an office in
the region to generate interest in bank activities within the
region.''
</P>
<P>
Last year only seven among the PTA bank's 15 member states
accessed the bank's project financing facilities.
</P>
<P>
This was the second consecutive year the bank has slowed down its
project financing operations in an attempt to consolidate project
monitoring and other credit delievery procedures.
</P>
<P>
The PTA Bank was formed in 1985 to further the aims of the
preferential trade area (now COMESA) by financing projects designed
to make the economies of member states complementary to each other.
enditem

