<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. Hopes "Democratic Transition" in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Upon the departure of Zairian
President Mobutu Sese Seko, U.S. President Bill Clinton said on
Friday that the United States would exert its efforts to help
Zaire on the road toward a "democratic transition."
</P>
<P>
"The United States' position is clear," Clinton said. "We want
to see a transition to a genuine democracy."
</P>
<P>
He pledged to "do what we can" to promote a "democratic
transition in one of the largest and most important nations in
Africa."
</P>
<P>
Mobutu flew off to Gbadolite, north of the capital of Kinshasa,
on Friday for what his spokesman called a "short rest."
</P>
<P>
Hours later, the information minister announced that Mobutu had
"ceased all intervention in the conduct of affairs of state."
</P>
<P>
"He reigns but does not govern," Information Minister Kin-Kiey
Mulumba told a press conference. He said Mobutu retains a title.
</P>
<P>
Clinton urged worldwide support for the efforts of South
African President Nelson Mandela, who he said had done "a superb
job" in trying to end the violent conflicts in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"I want the whole world to get behind him," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the
departure of President Mobutu Sese Seko "opens the way for a
peaceful resolution of the military conflict."
</P>
<P>
"We are at this stage working with all the parties so that we
can avoid bloodshed and also to do what can be done in terms of
contributing to a process that would be peaceful and have an
inclusive transition that would result in free and fair
elections," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I think the most important point here is that Zaire now
needs to move forward away from war towards peace, stability and
elections," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
