<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Leaves Middle East For Home Empty-Handed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace
coordinator Dennis Ross is leaving the region for home tonight
after failing to bridge the gaps between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived last week, met in his Jerusalem hotel with
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai early this morning to brief him
on his fruitless attempts in the past 24 hours to bring the two
parties back to talks, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Mordechai himself took part in a three-way
meeting at the residence of the U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin
Indyk in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai and Ross exchanged views and ideas on the
possibility of advancing the process with the Palestinians despite
what he called the existing gaps between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Later in the morning, Ross received the EU special envoy to
the Middle East peace process, Ambassador Miguel Angel
Moratinos. Moratinos said after the meeting that the situation was
not so bad.
</P>
<P>
"There is still a big gap. Two elements, land and security, are
two issues that have to be focused on in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, Ross met with Abu Mazen, PLO secretary
general. Originally, Ross was scheduled to hold talks with
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat Thursday night. But Arafat
called off the meeting, saying that the U.S. envoy was siding with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu told the
weekly cabinet meeting that there is no real progress in the
contacts between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
According to a cabinet statement, Netanyahu said that the
sides raised demands when they met this week, but the
Palestinians appear interested in what he called creating an
artificial crisis to prevent progress in the diplomatic
process.
</P>
<P>
Israel demanded security cooperation resume while the
Palestinian side asked for a halt to the settlement construction
in Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials complained that the U.S. had not pushed
Israel hard enought to stop its settlement expansion drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
