<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Dutch Proposal on Experts Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece today rejected a proposal by
the Dutch EU presidency for a direct meeting between the Greek-
Turkish Committees of Experts formed recently to examine the
differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the proposal that the two committees should meet
between May 26 and 28, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos
described the proposal as "naive" and "mistaken", saying that such
a meeting would serve "no useful purpose."
</P>
<P>
Pangalos confirmed that he received a letter today from his
Dutch counterpart Hans Van Mierlo proposing a direct meeting of
the two committees at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos stressed that first of all, the process of exchanging
views by correspondence must proceed.
</P>
<P>
"If the aim of the EU presidency is to exert pressure for the
commencement of direct talks, in order to secure the release of
the EU-Turkey financial protocol, then it is a naive approach,
because Greece has repeatedly stated that it will not consent to
the release of these funds unless Turkey satisfies the three
conditions set by Athens," he said.
</P>
<P>
He assured however that the procedure regarding the committees
would continue, adding that the letter of the Greek side would be
sent to the Dutch presidency at the beginning of next week, on the
condition however that the Van Mierlo proposal for a meeting of
the committees is withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
Athens has insisted that relations between Greece and Turkey
could be improved only if Ankara could meet the three conditions
set by Greece, namely Ankara must reject the use and threat of
force, respect international law and treaties, and have recourse
to the International Court at the Hague for the settlement of any
claims it might have. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-16 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Countries Involved Urged to Show Real Interest on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government has urged
all countries, which are involved in the Cyprus problem, to show
their actual interest in the planned direct talks between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing today, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides said that for the first time ever,
so many countries have simultaneously show their interest in a
Cyprus solution by appointing their own special representatives.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the countries, which have declared their intention
to help the U.N. Secretary-General's good offices mission, and
especially the Security council five permanent members, to show
in practical terms their real interest during direct talks,"
Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The direct talks would probably convene in late June.
</P>
<P>
"Wishful thinking has failed for decades to bring about a
settlement," the Spokesman said, adding that something more
decisive is needed.
</P>
<P>
Asked to explain the term "real interest", the Spokesman said
"this might be interventions, pressure on Turkey, Denktash and
other parties, to get replies to six or seven key questions on
Cyprus, pending for years."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Chief, he said, "takes the responsibility to issue
invitations to the two sides for direct talks as well as his own
share of responsibility in a possible failure".
</P>
<P>
However, Christofides made it clear that both the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides will also be responsible for an eventual
failure, if talks collapse.
</P>
<P>
After two-months of U.N.-led proximity talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is
expected to issue invitations to President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to have face-to-face talks
in June, possibly in New York.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Under-Secretary General Sir Kieran Prendergast is
currently in Cyprus for talks with Clerides and Denktash for
finishing touches on the proposed direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after the Turkish troops took control of its
northern third in the wake of a short-lived coup seeking union
with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
