<HEADLINE> UN Council Okays Increase of UN Police in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council on
Friday unanimously approved an increase in strength of U.N.
International Police Task Force in Bosnia by 120 police personnel
to enable it to carry out additional human rights and training
duties.
</P>
<P>
The council urged member states to provide qualified police
monitors and other forms of assistance and support to the
International Police Task Force.
</P>
<P>
By taking the move, the council gave all the additional police
force requested by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
In a March report, Annan suggested that the U.N. position more
police in the northwestern Bosnian city of Brcko, which according
to an arbitration award will remain under international control
for another year.
</P>
<P>
He also said a substantial number of police experts were needed
on human rights investigation, monitoring of the local police,
strengthening of police training, police restructuring and the
development of guidelines for democratic policing.
</P>
<P>
At the end of March, the council approved an earlier increase
of 186 additional police and 11 civilians for Brcko.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. police task force was set up in December, 1995
together with the 31,000-strong NATO-led Stabilization Force.
</P>
</TEXT>
