<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Leader Ready to Attend Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has announced that its
state leader will stop boycotting future Arab summit attended by
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Official Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) today quoted Kuwaiti acting
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad as
saying that "I say Kuwait has no right to ban any conference or
object on that."
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahmad underlined in an interview with Lebanese weekly
Al-Sheraa published today "Kuwait's readiness to participate in an
Arab summit attended by the Iraqi regime's president."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait was occupied by Iraqi troops under the order of Saddam
Hussein in 1990 and was declared the 19th province of Iraq for
seven months before it was liberated by an U.S.-led
multi-national coalition force from the occupation in the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
Since the Gulf War in 1991, Kuwaiti leaders boycott any
occasions of Arabian major political forums or economic functions
with the presence of Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Abdullaziz
Al-Dakheel told a press conference last Thursday that Kuwait
would not obstruct re-establishment of Arab unification and
asserted that the Gulf state has adamantly called for preserving
territorial unity of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
