<HEADLINE> U.N. Official: Direct Talks Likely to Start Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Under-Secretary General for
Political Affairs, Sir Kieran Prendergast, announced here today
that the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities are
willing to go to direct talks on the Cyprus problem..
</P>
<P>
He also said the talks, aiming to resume a process to search
for a comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus problem, are likely
to start in Late June or early July.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official made the remarks at a press conference at the
end of his two-day visit to the island, where he had separate
meetings with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that no preconditions are set for this
process by either leader, who are likely to meet first in "a
secluded venue" near New York and continue talks in Europe,
probably Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"I found my contacts with the two leaders to be both valuable
and informative," Sir Kieran said, noting he is in a better
position to report back to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan next
week.
</P>
<P>
Annan will have to take a firm decision at the end of the
month, Sir Kieran explained and pointed out that "the
Secretary-General himself has made it clear that he would like to
see direct talks resume by the middle of this year."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said the aim of renewed direct talks is "a
comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus problem and we at the
U.N. will do our very best to promote such an outcome, but
ultimately success depends on the willingness of the two sides to
show flexibility and willingness to compromise."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.N. considered that now it was closer to
progress, Sir Kieran replied "if we did not think there was a
chance of progress, we would not issue an invitation."
</P>
<P>
He also said key players in the Cyprus problem, including the
European Union, Greece, Turkey and Britain as well as the U.S.,
will be in the wings for consultations, if need be.
</P>
<P>
Sir Kieran will leave Sunday for Athens for talks with Greek
officials, and then fly on to Ankara for meetings Tuesday with
Turkish government officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
