<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Apologizes to Tuskegee Experiment Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday apologized to black men whose syphilis went untreated by
government doctors.
</P>
<P>
In an address at a White House ceremony, Clinton said, the
victims were "betrayed," and "Their lives were trampled upon."
</P>
<P>
With aged victims of the Tuskegee Syphilis Study conducted
between the 1930s and 1972 seated in the East Room, the president
said, "What was done cannot be undone but we can end the silence."
</P>
<P>
"We can look at you in the eyes and finally say on behalf of
the American people: What the government did was shameful and I am
sorry," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the president, Herman Shaw, a victim of the study
said, "We were treated unfairly -- to some extend like guinea pigs."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We were not pigs. We were not dancing boys."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also announced an effort today to encourage more blacks
to pursue careers in bioethics and medical research.
</P>
<P>
He promised a 200,000-dollar planning grant to allow Tuskegee
University to pursue building a Center for Bioethics in Research
and Health Care. The White House said the center would serve as a
"lasting memorial" that would "address the legacy of the syphilis
study."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also announced the creation of bioethics fellowships
for minority students, offered by the Department of Health and
Human Services. He directed HHS Secretary Donna Shalala to draft a
report within 180 days outlining ways to better involve all
communities, especially minority communities, in research and
health care.
</P>
<P>
The president also has planned a major initiative on race,
starting with a June 14 speech at the University of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Clinton told Shaw, Carter Howard, 93; Charlie Pollard,
91; Herman Shaw, 94; and Fred Simmons, 100, that the United States
is officially sorry that it let them suffer so unfairly for so
long during the Tuskegee Syphilis Study.
</P>
<P>
Other survivors and their families, unable to make the trip,
watched the ceremony via satellite from the campus of Tuskegee
University.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in the 1930s, 399 men signed up with the U.S. Public
Health Service for free medical care. The service was conducting a
study on the effects of syphilis on the human body and, at the
time, the sexually transmitted disease was rampant in Macon
County, Alabama.
</P>
<P>
But the men were never told they had syphilis. They were told
they had "bad blood" and were denied access to treatment, even for
years after penicillin came into use in 1947.
</P>
<P>
By 1972, 28 men had died of syphilis, 100 others were dead of
related complications, at least 40 wives had been infected and 19
children had contracted the disease at birth.
</P>
<P>
The government has never actually admitted wrongdoing, though
it has distributed about 10 million dollars to more than 6,000
survivors and their family members after settling a 1973
class-action lawsuit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
