<HEADLINE> Croatian FM Defends Against U.S. Criticism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Croatian Foreign
Minister Mate Granic today defended his country against criticism
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Granic said he was mystified by
the comments of State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns that the
Croatian leader's meeting Thursday with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright revealed broad disagreement between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Burns said, "I can't remember a tougher meeting in
a long time that the secrtary's had with a visiting foreign
minister."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, featured as a "vigorous discussion back and
forth", Albright made it "crystal clear" to Granic that Croatia
cannot be treated as a friend so long as it does not abide by the
Dayton peace agreement, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Disagreeing with Burns' comment, Granic told reporters,
however, there was agreement on more than 90 percent of the issues
discussed, and he was satisfied with the meeting.
</P>
<P>
As for Burns' allegation of mistreatment of the minority
Serbian population in Croatia, Granic said Croatia is doing all it
can to ensure that all displaced people can return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
