<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Urged to Surrender Illegal Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government today gave
orders to the people in six districts in northwestern Kenya to
hand over their illegal firearms.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, Jackson Kalweo,
Minister in the Office of the President in charge of internal
security, said that the government had mounted security operations in the
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Of late, the minister noted, there had been several
incidents of banditry and cattle rustling in the districts of
Marakwet, West Pokot, Samburu, Turkana, Marsabit and Isiolo.
</P>
<P>
The banditry and cattle rustling have led to loss of human
lives, theft of livestock and rendered many people homeless, he
stated.
</P>
<P>
Kalweo pointed out that the on-going security operations
launched by the government were
designed to arrest the perpetrators of the crimes, and to recover
illegal firearms and stolen livestock.
</P>
<P>
The minister reaffirmed the government's commitment in
apprehending all those possessing illegal firearms and called on
communities in areas bordering neighbouring countries not
to take the law into their hands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
