<HEADLINE> Lockheed Martin Remains US Largest Defense Contractor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. remained
the U.S largest defense contractor for the second successive year,
the Pentagon announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The annual listing of major defense contractors by the Pentagon
showed that Lockheed had 12 billion U.S. dollars in contracts in
1996, up from 10.5 billion dollars in the previous year. The
figures cover the fiscal year ending September 30.
</P>
<P>
McDonnell Douglas Corp. held its No. 2 position with 9.9
billion dollars in contracts.
</P>
<P>
Lockheed beat out McDonnell Douglas for first place in the
previous year after it was combined by Lockheed Corp. and Martin
Marietta Corp. The company is now based in Bethesda, Maryland
state.
</P>
<P>
The giant makes a wide range of military hardware, including
Trident and Hellfire missiles, the C-5 Galaxy transport plane, the
F-16 Falcon and F-22 Raptor fighter jets and communications gear
for defense satellites.
</P>
<P>
McDonnell Douglas, which is based in St. Louis, produces the
Navy's F-18 Hornet fighter, the Air Force's F-15 Eagle fighter,
the C-17 transport, the Army's Apache helicopter and missiles,
including the Tomahawk and Harpoon.
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp., Detroit, climbed up from fourth to third
place with 3.2 billion dollars in contracts, up from 3 billion
dollars the year before. It makes power transmission components
for the Army's Abrams tanks and other parts for Bradley Fighting
Vehicles, as well as other missiles and aircraft parts.
</P>
<P>
In fourth place was Raytheon Corp., maker of the Patriot air
defense system and other missiles as well as defense electronics,
with 3 billion dollars in contracts.
</P>
<P>
One big winner was General Dynamics Corp., maker of Abrams
tanks, Seawolf attack submarines, Aegis destroyers and Stinger and
Tomahawk missiles. It rose from 11th to fifth place, with 2.7
billion dollars in contracts, up from 1.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The other giant military companies also include: Northrop
Grumman, whose products include the B-2 stealth bomber and the MX
missile system as well as defense electronics; United Technologies
Corp., maker of military aircraft engines and components,
helicopters and defense electronics; the Boeing Co., which makes
numerous military aircraft; Litton Industries Inc., maker of Aegis
destroyers, ships and other aircraft; and General Electric Co.,
which makes many aircraft engines and missile components. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
