<HEADLINE> Britain's New FM Pays First Visit to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook is expected to arrive here Monday for his first
official visit to the United States to talk about European
security affairs with senior U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Cook and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will meet
to "further strengthen" the special British-U.S. relations, U.S.
State Department Spokesman Nicholas Burns announced here today.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary welcomes this early opportunity to consult with
Secretary Cook and to further strengthen the very warm, special
productive ties between the United States and the United Kingdom,"
Burns added.
</P>
<P>
Cook and Albright will discuss a wide range of subjects,
including the recent agreement reached between Russia and the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and Bosnia issues.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the U.S.-British relations, Burns said, "I think
there's a sense in our government that we're going to work very
well with Prime Minister Blair and Foreign Minister Cook."
</P>
<P>
Burns stressed that his country and Britain have been enjoying
a "special relationship" and will continue to do so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
