<HEADLINE> US Disappointed With Mideast Peace Stagnation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States, disappointed
with the stalled Middle East peace process, today called on
Israelis and Palestinians to re-open their negotiations so that
the peace process could be pulled back on track.
</P>
<P>
Before her talks with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters, "There
continues to be a need to bring the parties together in a
constructive dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told
reporters at a briefing that the peace process between the
Palestinians and Israel had "not moved forward for months."
</P>
<P>
He said, "Minister Levy and Secretary Albright discussed at
some length the efforts by the United States, Israel and the
Palestinians to revive the peace negotiations."
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross, who arrived in the Middle East
early this month in an attempt to bring the Palestinians and
Israelis back to the negotiating table, has failed in doing his
mission and will return to Washington to report to the president
and the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
Ross was said to be snubbed by Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, who said in a letter to President Bill Clinton that he was
disappointed with Ross's mission.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian officials said Ross had not been pushing
Israel hard enough to comply with the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians negotiators have said they would not resume peace
talks and security cooperation, suspended two months ago, unless
Israel stopped construction of Jewish neighborhood in Arab east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian negotiators were surprised when Ross kept
silent at Israeli officials' remarks during a high-level meeting
between the two sides that they would continue building Jewish
settlements both in east Jerusalem and on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Albright also will discuss with Levy on upgrading aid to Jordan
as a sort of reward for King Hussein who managed to bring Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Arafat
together to sign an agreement on Hebron early this year.
</P>
<P>
One option under consideration is to shift some of the 3
billion dollars Israel gets annually to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Levy said more aid to Jordan was an important link to the peace
process and "we will find a common way to achieve that goal."
</P>
<P>
Albright said, "We are now examining with the Israelis details
on how best to move forward on this, and when we reach a
conclusion on this, we'll be consulting with Congress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
