<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Reforms to Yield 100 Mln Dlr Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Managerial reform in the
United Nations would yield savings of 100 million dollars this
year, or 7.7 percent of its annual regular budget, and improve the
world body's effectiveness, a top UN official said here today.
</P>
<P>
In his introduction to the report at the Fifth Committee
(Administrative and Budgetary) this morning,
Under-Secretary-General Joseph E. Connor said that reform efforts
were laying the groundwork for "keeping within a `no growth'
budget, living with reduced staff levels and for future savings."
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "UN 21: Accelerating Managerial Reform for
Results," laid out key goals designed to accelerate and integrate
managerial reform, streamline administration; modernize and
enhance information services; and align responsibility and
accountability.
</P>
<P>
As part of the reform efforts to streamline administration,
some offices had already achieved required budget reductions for
1996-1997 and laid the basis for 1998-1999 savings through
enhanced efficiency, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The efforts to modernize and enhance information services
included those that had made the UN home page a top-rated Internet
site, consulted more than a million times a week as of February,
up from about 200,000 a week in last June. The home page and other
electronic publications had put the organization on track to
achieve 25 percent reduction in the volume of paper documents by
1998 while improving its capacity to service member states.
</P>
<P>
Conner said that by the end of June, every mission in New York
would be connected to the UN home page and to all UN documents on
the Optical Disk System via the Internet. By the end of the year,
every mission in Geneva and Vienna would be connected.
</P>
<P>
The reforms had delivered results which included savings of at
least 30 million dollars in regular and extrabudgetary efficiency
savings last year and about 100 million dollars expected savings
this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The UN's current annual regular budget stands at 1.3 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
