<HEADLINE> Mobutu May Go Into Exile in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Zaire's ousted president Mobutu Sese
Seko might seek exile in France after brief stays in Morocco and
Liechtenstein, Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted a reliable source
in the Moroccan capital Rabat as saying today.
</P>
<P>
But the statement made hours ago by the the country's new
self-appointed leader, Laurent Kabila that Mobutu can stay in
Gbadolite, northern Zaire, could change the "information on the
problem," AFP quoted the unidentified diplomat in Rabat as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu will stay in Morocco anything from several hours to a
few days, because he cannot immediately go to France, which is at
the height of its legislative election campaign, said the source.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry spokesman said he had no indications
of whether Mobutu, who ruled Zaire for 32 years, might seek exile
in France.
</P>
<P>
An American diplomat in Rabat said today that Mobutu would
arrive "within hours" in Morocco, which has prepared a villa for
him in a residential district of Rabat.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted an African diplomat in Rabat as saying that "an
advisor for the military security" of Mobutu and several of his
relatives would be in Rabat today.
</P>
<P>
Morocco has officially neither denied nor confirmed the reports.
</P>
<P>
The forces of Laurent Kabila's Alliance of Democratic
Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) today entered
Kinshasa after an eight-month rebellion against the government.
</P>
<P>
Kabila also declared himself the new head of state of Zaire and
said the country would now be known as the Democratic Republic of
Congo, the former name of Zaire scrapped by Mobutu in 1971. 
</P>
</TEXT>
