<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM, EU Envoy Review Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
and European Union Mideast Envoy Miguel Moratinos today reviewed
the latest developments on the Palestinian-Israeli track, after
the latest U.S. efforts failed to restore the peace momentum.
</P>
<P>
In statements to reporters following the meeting, Moratinos
said the peace process has to be rescued and the EU will exert
all efforts via diplomatic channels to this end.
</P>
<P>
Carrying a message from Cairo that the peace process is in the
most critical stage since Madrid, the EU envoy said he will head
Sunday to Gaza then Israel and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is important to activate the role of
Russia as a co-sponsor of the peace process at such a critical
stage.
</P>
<P>
It is possible that he will return to Cairo after calling an
emergency meeting of senior European officials next week, to take
the right decision on following steps.
</P>
<P>
"There is no time left to waste and it is necessary to get out
of such serious situation," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
As for the role that could be played by the European side
after the failure of the mission of U.S. Peace Coordinator Dennis
Ross, Moratinos said the European stance and the U.S. role are
not contradictory.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the EU is "deeply concerned over the
impasse of the peace drive, especially on the Palestinian track."
</P>
<P>
He said his meeting with Moussa today was a good opportunity
to directly expound issues and suggest ideas.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos arrived here Friday, a day after Ross returned home
empty-handed after a renewed shuttle diplomacy between Israeli
and Palestinian leaders in a bid to breathe new life to the peace
talks stalled since Israel broke ground for a new Jewish
settlement in East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The nine-day American mediation failed as Israel rejected a
call for the halt of the construction. The Palestinians
reportedly accused Ross of siding with Israel on the settlement
issue.
</P>
<P>
Amid signs of escalating crisis, President of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat has demanded personal
involvement of U.S. President Bill Clinton to save the peace
process, according to the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called on the U.S. to play a more active role in its
mediation efforts, while meeting with Ross in the West Bank city
of Nablus Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Ross had met with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai as well as the EU envoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
