<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Project for Poor Areas Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The latest statistics show that
some poor areas in China have received over 2.6 billion yuan
(about 320 million US dollars) to support a project to bring them
nine-year compulsory education during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The project was jointly launched by the State Education
Commission (SEC) and the Ministry of Finance in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Baoqing, vice-minister in charge of the SEC, said here
today that 22,766 schools have become beneficiaries of the
project. In addition, 9,318 new schools have been built in poor
areas in the past two years. Local teachers have received
professional training.
</P>
<P>
In May 1996 a total of 12 provinces including north China's
Hebei and Shanxi, central China's Henan, northwest China's Shaanxi
and northeast China's Heilongjiang, signed an agreement with the
SEC and the Ministry of Finance to enhance the education project.
</P>
<P>
Soon after that, 383 counties in the 12 provinces started to
carry out the project. According to the agreement, the 12
provinces will receive and allocate 5.3 billion yuan of project
funds by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics provided by the 383 counties, the
enrollment rate for school-age children increased to 98.7 percent
in 1996 from 1994's 97.27 percent. The dropout rate among primary
school students dropped to 1.16 percent last year from 1.81
percent in 1994. The enrollment rate at junior middle schools
reached 85.3 percent last year from 77.73 percent. The dropout
rate decreased to 2.71 percent in 1996 from 4.53 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It is planned that by the year 2000 the central government will
allocate 3.9 billion yuan to support compulsory education in some
590 poor counties designated by central and provincial
governments. Meanwhile, local governments are urged to allocate
twice as much as the central government does to aid education.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the project is expected to be supplied with nearly
12 billion yuan by the year 2000, making it the largest
educational project launched by the Chinese government since 1949.
</P>
<P>
The project will shift its focus to nine poor provinces and
autonomous regions in the western part of the country from next
year, including the Inner Mongolia and Guangxi Zhuang autonomous
regions, and Yunnan and Guizhou provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
