<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nigeria's New Rows With Britain, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Yongkang)
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's strained relations with
Britain and the U.S. received a further blow in the last few
days, following Libyan leader Colonel Muammar Ghaddafi's visit to
the west African country.
</P>
<P>
While Colonel Ghaddafi was still in Niamey of Niger, the U.S.
had reportedly made a request to the Nigerian government to
detain Ghaddafi's plane for violating the United Nations' air
embargo.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government regarded this as interference of its
internal affairs, because Ghaddafi's visit was arranged at its
invitation.
</P>
<P>
When Ghaddafi arrived in Kano Airport in northern Nigeria on
May 9 aboard a Libyan Airlines plane, escorted by seven other
Libyan planes, he was given everything that a head of state
deserves at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Ghaddafi was also greeted by thousands of Nigerian Muslims on
his way to the Kano State Government House, for he had come to
celebrate the Muslim New Year and many Muslims are said to be
sympathetic to him, regarding him as a victim of U.S. policies.
</P>
<P>
After condemning U.S. policy of producing instability in
Islamic countries at a rally and holding talks with Nigerian head
of state, General Sani Abacha, Ghaddafi got on board his plane in
the company of Abacha and flew to the Nigerian capital, Abuja.
</P>
<P>
There, he was given a grand state banquet and was even honored
with the Grand Commander of the Federal Republic, one of the
highest national honors of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was apparently angered by this move. It condemned
Ghaddafi's trip and persuaded the United Nations Sanctions
Committee into a probe into the roles of Niger and Nigeria in the
event.
</P>
<P>
The situation on the British front is even worse.
</P>
<P>
On May 12, Britain's new Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, while
explaining the Labor government's foreign policy, announced that
the new government will retain the sanctions imposed on Nigeria
by the Conservative government since 1993.
</P>
<P>
"There should be tough economic sanctions on a regime which is
among the most brutal in the world," he allegedly said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's anger and disappointment to this is apparent. It
should be recalled that not long before, General Abacha had sent
a congratulatory message to Tony Blair for his party's victory in
the British elections.
</P>
<P>
The final showdown between Nigeria and Britain seemed to be
imminent on Friday, when the British government informed Nigeria
early that day of its decision to ban Nigerian planes from flying
to London.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had already done the same in November 1993, following
the annulment of the June 12 presidential elections by the then
Babangida government of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria reponded quickly. On Friday afternoon, the British
Airways in Lagos was informed by the Ministry of Aviation of its
decision to stop the airlines and all British registered planes
from flying to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Though there are worries of Nigeria's "showdown with the
west", analysts here believe that nothing serious will come out
of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Aderemi Oyewumi of the Nigerian Institute of International
Affairs admitted that Nigeria's warm reception for one of
America's "greatest enemy" will have a negative effect on its
relations with the U.S.
</P>
<P>
But he said nothing serious may come of the UN Sanctions
Committee and the Security Council other than mere condemnations.
</P>
<P>
"There is no much they can do to Ghaddafi and even Nigeria,"
he said, "Many African countries are against the U.N. resolution
on Libya and believe that Libya has been singled out for
victimization by the west."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
