<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Not to Alter Under Pressures, Says Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will only do business with
countries that respect its sovereignty and relate to it on the
basis of equality, head of state General Sani Abacha has said.
</P>
<P>
The federal government will not be altered through external
pressures from its set course to which it is irredeemably
committed, Abacha was quoted by the local paper "Guardian" today
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The countries with which Nigeria would do business must stand
by it and fulfill all their promises, Abacha added.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of an address by the head of state at
the launching of 1,500 specialized vehicles for the use of the
armed forces and police on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The troop and personnel carriers, supplied by the Tata
Engineering and Locomotive Company Ltd of India, will enable the
armed forces and police to be well equipped to play greater
regional peacekeeping roles, Abacha said.
</P>
<P>
"With regional conflicts in Africa increasingly becoming
purely African affairs, the Nigerian Araed forces and police will
have a greater role to play in regional peacekeeping," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
