<HEADLINE> Kenya Committed to Reducing Drop-out Rate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Education Minister Joseph
Kamotho said that his government is concerned with the
enrollment rate in both primary and secondary schools and
committed to reversing the trend of declining rate.
</P>
<P>
The "Daily Nation" today quoted the minister as saying in
Nyeri, 150 kilometers north of Nairobi, that the government will
continue to implement the secondary school bursary program
started in 1993/94 financial year.
</P>
<P>
He told a head-teachers meeting that the government had spent
a total amount of about 18 million U.S. Dollars for the program
which is designed to help students who are unable to pay school
fees.
</P>
<P>
In 1993/94, a total of 3 million Dollars was disbursed to the
needy and the figure rose to 4 million Dollars in the next two
years respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996/97 financial year, the minister noted, the
government gave out more than 7 million Dollars in order to
reduce the drop-out rate in schools.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the government intends to embark on
strategies for providing good general education which will
generate broad social benefits to the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the greatest importance of education to
the industrialization process in the country is the assured
supply of well-trained managers, skilled technicians and
entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
