<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors to Fix Funding Strategy for Energy Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Donors to Bangladesh are expected to
fix a strategy for future lending to the country's energy sector
at a four-day meeting beginning here on May 19, said an official
of the Asian Development Bank (ADB) resident mission.
</P>
<P>
The ADB, the biggest lending agency in the energy sector of
Bangladesh, will coordinate the meeting to be attended by the
major donors including the World Bank (WB), Germany, the United
Kingdom, Japan and Norway which have invested in Bangladesh's
energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The ADB official said the basic objectives of the meeting are
to review the energy sector's performance, the status of the
ongoing projects and progress of sector reforms and fixing a
strategy for future lending to the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Two sessions of the meeting will take place between Bangladesh
and the donors while the others will be held among the donors.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Energy and Mineral Resources Nooruddin Khan is
expected to preside over a session on the first day between
Bangladesh and the donors. Bangladesh will present two papers
respectively on the gas and power sector at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has already prepared a review report on the basis of
the said objectives and the report will be submitted to the
meeting, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The donors' lending to the energy sector may increase in view
of the congenial investment climate created following the
initiative of subregional cooperation made by Bangladesh, India,
Nepal and Bhutan, the official added.
</P>
<P>
At present, the contributions of the two major donor agencies,
the World Bank and the ADB, to Bangladesh's energy sector stand at
2.1 billion U.S. dollars, of which the ADB has a share of 1.1
billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
