<HEADLINE> Local Elections in West Nepal Go Smoothly: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Local polls went smoothly in
general in West Nepal today despite a few reported incidents of
confrontation between workers of different political parties,
official sources said.
</P>
<P>
About 55 percent of more than 5 million eligible voters cast
their ballots today in the first phase of the local elections in
1,800 villages and 24 municipalities in West Nepal's 40 districts,
according to an official of the Election Commission here.
</P>
<P>
Polling station confrontation between workers of major
political parties was reported at 30 villages and two
municipalities and the elections there have been postponed, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Election officers, volunteers and police personnel were active
in ensuring that the polls were conducted in a peaceful manner
while political workers were seen busy taking voters to polling
stations, the official news agency RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen people were injured in the western city of Nepalgunj,
about 300 kilometers from here, in the afternoon when two factions
clashed at a polling station, leading to an overnight curfew
imposed by the local authorities, the RSS reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the Election Commission's arrangements, the second phase
of the elections will be held in Central and East Nepal on May 26.
</P>
<P>
During the two-phase elections, Nepali voters would elect about
180,000 officials for more than 4,000 local administration bodies
at village, municipality and district levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
