<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Central Bank of Jordan (CBJ) will keep unchanged
the interest rates on Jordanian dinar and the dinar-dollar
exchange rate, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates in Jordan had no relation to those in the
United states and the fixed exchange rate had been in force for
the past two years and there is no intention to change it, said
Walid Khairallah, the CBJ deputy governor.
</P>
<P>
The CBJ made the declaration against rumors that the bank
increased the interest rates on dinars over the past few months
to give the dinar holders better advantage over those who held
U.S. dollar deposits and the fixed dollar-dinar exchange rate was
to be changed in response to the higher value of the dollar on
international markets.
</P>
<P>
In Jordan's banks, the interest rates of fixed dinar deposit
are a few points higher than that of dollars.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Central Bank of Jordan (CBJ) will in the coming
four to five months offer Jordanian government bonds worth 70
million U.S. dollars to potential investors on the world markets,
according to Jordan Times today.
</P>
<P>
The decision is aimed at helping the country reach a level of
self-sustenance, when it will no longer be in need of support to
finance its balance of payment deficit, said CBJ Deputy Governor
Michael Marto.
</P>
<P>
Marto made the remarks at an investment seminar organized by a
Swiss Bank in London to help Jordan attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Germany have signed a 102 million DM
(about 61 million U.S. dollars) protocol slated to cover debt
alleviation, soft loans and grants to be used in water projects
and poverty eradication programs, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among the amount, 50 million DM (about 30 million dollars) is
German's allocation for Jordan in 1997, 12 million DM (about 7
million dollars) for technical assistance and 40 million DM
(about 24 million dollars) for relieving the country's debt to
Germany, according to the protocol signed here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the third largest aid contributor to Jordan after
the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian government would provide all lands for
Egyptian, Arab and foreign investors in the southern Nile Valley
area for reclamation and establishment of investment ventures,
the Arabic newspaper Akhbar El Yom today quoted Minister of
Cabinet Affairs Talaat Hamaad as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hammad said that these ventures would enjoy all incentives and
privileges foremost among which is a 20-year tax holiday.
</P>
<P>
He said that applicants would obtain lands according to
available area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
