<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila Declares Himself Head of Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The 32-year rule of Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko came to an end today as Zaire's capital
fell to the forces led by Laurent-Desire Kabila, who declared
himself the head of state of ``the Democratic Republic of Congo.''
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who heads the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of Congo-Zaire, declared himself head of state at a
press conference in the southern city of Lubumbashi this morning.
</P>
<P>
He also declared that the country would no longer be called
Zaire -- the name Mobutu gave it in 1971 -- but would be known as
the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Congo was the name used by the country after independence in
1960 and before Mobutu took power.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's announcement came after an eight-month battle across
the country to defeat government troops and oust Mobutu, his rival
for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's soldiers were seen to be moving close to the center of
Kinshasa, while unarmed government soldiers, disguised as
civilians and carrying sacks on their shoulders, were fleeing the
city.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between government troops and Kabila's forces
continued from Friday until this morning around Kinshasa's
international airport, 25 kilometers north of the city, and
government forces looted the center of the capital this morning.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's troops had ordered government soldiers to lay down their
arms before 11:00 (10:00 GMT), and there was panic at their
headquarters as officers prepared to flee.
</P>
<P>
The streets were deserted, and many young people stood at the
doors of their houses anticipating the arrival of the rebels with
a look of indifference on their faces.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable sources reached by telephone, Prime
Minister General Likoulia Bolongo has fled to neighboring
Congo, while Defense Minister General Mahele Liyoko was killed by
soldiers early this morning at an army camp.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu fled the city on Friday for his jungle palace in his
home region of Gbadolite and is expected to seek asylum in
Morocco, where he owns a residence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
