<HEADLINE> Taiwan Stunt Driver to Leap Hukou Waterfall as Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Daredevil Ke Shouliang reaffirmed
here Friday that his attempt to jump across the Hukou Waterfall in
a stunt car will go ahead as scheduled on June 1.
</P>
<P>
He said he would do his last test run by jumping across a 50-m
gap -- the width of the waterfall -- next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ke's family will be there June 1 to witness his attempt, Ke
said in this capital of north China's Shanxi Province Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 44-year-old stuntman hopes that this will mark a
triumphant end to his dangerous career.
</P>
<P>
The waterfall lies on the border between Shanxi and Shaanxi
provinces, with a drop of over 30 m.
</P>
<P>
Ke will drive his car along a ramp 264 m long and 10 m wide on
the Shanxi side and launch it into the air over the waterfall.
</P>
<P>
He hopes to land on a platform 50 m long and 10 m wide on the
Shaanxi side, which will be cushioned with cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the China Central Television Station will carry a
four-hour live telecast of the event, and the Phoenix Television
Station of Hong Kong will broadcast the event live overseas.
</P>
<P>
Ke failed in his first test run in March, but jumped 42 m
during the second test run in early April.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 he drove a motorcycle across the Jinshanling Section of
the Great Wall in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
