<HEADLINE> PLC Reads Bill on Provisional Regional Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Regional Council (Amendment)
Bill 1997 was tabled here today by the Chief Executive's Office of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) to the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) for the first and second
readings.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the seventh PLC plenary meeting, Michael Suen,
secretary for policy coordination of the Chief Executive's Office,
outlined the main contents of the draft bill:
</P>
<P>
-- The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the
existing Regional Council, which is to stop functioning on June
30, 1997, will be assigned to the Provisional Regional Council so
as to achieve a seamless transition.
</P>
<P>
-- The Provisional Regional Council consists of not more than
50 members, a 25 percent increase compared with the existing
Regional Council. The members will be appointed by the Chief
Executive with their terms of office running not later than
December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
-- A person appointed does not become a member and cannot
undertake any function as a member until he is sworn in.
</P>
<P>
-- The first meeting of the Provisional Regional Council will
be arranged before July 7, 1997, to elect a chairman and a
vice-chairman of the body.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Council is responsible for all matters concerning
environmental hygiene, public health, sanitation and the provision
of recreation, sports and cultural facilities and services to the
residents living in the New Territories.
</P>
<P>
According to Suen, the proposed Provisional Regional Council
will operate along with the establishment of the HKSAR in place of
the existing Regional Council .
</P>
<P>
Considering that the tenure of office of the existing Regional
Council ends on June 30, 1997 and that members of the first
Regional Council of the HKSAR can not be elected before July 1,
1997, it is necessary to set up the Provisional Regional Council
so as to fill a vacuum and guarantee an effective operation of the
HKSAR, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
