<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill on HKSAR Provisional District Boards Introduced to PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The District Boards (Amendment)
Bill 1997, which concerns the formation of 18 Provisional District
Boards throughout Hong Kong, was tabled here today to the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) for first and second
readings.
</P>
<P>
Michael Suen, secretary for policy coordination of the Chief
Executive's Office of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), explained the main contents of the draft bill at a PLC
plenary meeting:
</P>
<P>
-- Each Provisional District Board consists of not more than 40
members, a 25-percent increase over the existing District
Board. The members will be appointed by the chief executive with
their terms of office running not later than December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
-- A person appointed does not become a member and cannot
undertake any function as a member until he is sworn in.
</P>
<P>
-- The first meeting of the Provisional District Boards will be
arranged before July 7, 1997, to elect a chairman for each of the
boards.
</P>
<P>
The District Boards have a mainly advisory role with
substantial responsibility for the management of district affairs
and they provide a forum for public consultation and participation
at the district level.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the District Boards (Amendment) Bill 1997, two
other bills concerning the formation of provisional regional and
district organizations, the Urban Council (Amendment) Bill 1997
and the Regional Council (Amendment) Bill 1997, were also
introduced to today's meeting for first and second readings.
</P>
<P>
The existing 18 District Boards in Hong Kong, set up and formed
in accordance with the District Board Ordinance, will stop
functioning on June 30, 1997, in line with a resolution by the
Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress, Suen
said.
</P>
<P>
As members of the first District Boards can not be elected
before July 1, 1997, Provisional District Boards must be formed
along with the establishment of the HKSAR so as to avoid a vacuum
and guarantee the effective operation of the HKSAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
