<HEADLINE> Kabila Pledges to Form Government of National Salvation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Laurent-Desire Kabila today declared
himself the country's new head of state, suspended the
constitution and said he would form a government of "national
salvation" within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who heads the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of Congo-Zaire, said that the generals of the Zairean
government forces had pledged loyalty to him and ordered their
soldiers to surrender.
</P>
<P>
He said a parliament would be put into place within two months
and asked state employees in Kinshasa, which fell to his forces
today, to stay in their posts.
</P>
<P>
The new government would honor international obligations as
long as they conformed with the country's national interests.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Zaire's second largest city
Lubumbashi, his power base in the south, Kabila also announced the
country would be revert to the name Congo, used after independence
in 1960, and would now be known as the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
President Mobutu Sese Seko, who has ruled the country for 32
years, named the country Zaire in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who led the AFDL during its eight-month armed campaign
against Mobutu's government, said the leaders of the rebellion had
decided that he should assume from today the functions of chief of
the Congolese state.''
</P>
<P>
He said that Mobutu, who fled Kinshasa on Friday to his
stronghold of Gbadolite in northern Zaire, could remain in the
village. Mobutu, though, is expected to go into exile in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Kabila would travel to Kinshasa "very soon". 
</P>
</TEXT>
