<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Council (Amendment) Bill Tabled to PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Urban Council (Amendment) Bill
1997 was submitted to the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC)
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) here today
for first and second readings.
</P>
<P>
Michael Suen, secretary for policy coordination of the Chief
Executive's Office of the HKSAR, outlined the background for
drafting the bill and two other bills -- the Regional Council
(Amendment) Bill 1997 and the District Boards (Amendment) Bill
1997 -- at the seventh PLC plenary meeting.
</P>
<P>
The existing Urban Council, Regional Council and 18 District
Boards in Hong Kong were set up and formed in accordance with the
Urban Council Ordinance, the Regional Council Ordinance and the
District Board Ordinance respectively, Suen said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a resolution adopted by the Standing Committee of
China's National People's Congress (NPC) on August 31, 1994,
ruled that these regional and district organizations, the last
under British rule, will stop functioning on June 30, 1997, and
that the rights and duties and formation of the regional and
district organizations of the HKSAR will be stipulated by HKSAR
laws.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that on February 23, 1997, the Chinese legislature
decided that articles concerning election in the Urban Council
Ordinance, the Regional Council Ordinance and the District Board
Ordinance will not be adopted as HKSAR laws due to the fact that
they run against the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the tenure of the current Urban Council, Regional
Council and District Boards will end on June 30, 1997, and that
members of the first regional and district organizations of the
HKSAR can not be elected before July 1, 1997. Therefore, it is
necessary to set up provisional regional and district
organizations, namely, the Provisional Urban Council, the
Provisional Regional Council and 18 Provisional District Boards,
upon the establishment of the HKSAR so as to fill the vacuum and
guarantee the effective operation of the HKSAR, he said.
</P>
<P>
Suen summarized the main contents of the Urban Council
(Amendment) Ordinance 1997:
</P>
<P>
-- The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the
existing Urban Council will be assigned to the Provisional Urban
Council so as to achieve a smooth transition. The Urban Council is
responsible for matters concerning public health, sanitation and
hygiene, the provision of recreational, sports and cultural
facilities and activities in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
-- The Provisional Urban Council consists of not more than 50
members, a 25-percent increase over the existing Urban
Council. The members will be appointed by the chief executive with
their terms of office running not later than December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
-- A person appointed does not become a member and cannot
undertake any function as a member until he is sworn in.
</P>
<P>
-- The first meeting of the Provisional Urban Council will be
arranged before July 7, 1997, to elect a chairman and a
vice-chairman for the body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
