<HEADLINE> Russian Defense Minister Pledges to Cut Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia Defense Minister Igor Rodionov
pledged today to cut the number of Russian troops, including those
stationed in four Russian-held islands claimed by Japan, Kyodo
News reported.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov made the promise during a meeting with Japanese
Defense Agency chief Fumio Kyuma at the Defense Agency, Kyodo
quoted agency officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov, who arrived in Japan on Friday for a three-day visit,
is the first defense minister ever to visit Japan from Russia or
its predecessor, the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Russia has already cut its military personnel by 1.5 million
and plans to reduce numbers by another 200,000 this year, Rodionov
was quoted as telling Kyuma.
</P>
<P>
Defense Agency officials did not say whether Rodionov gave any
specific figures about the size of troops reductions on what Japan
calls its "northern Territories" which includes four islands
seized by the Soviet Union at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,500 Russian troops are stationed on the Japanese claimed
islands, according to Japanese Defense Agency.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Rodionov also briefed Kyuma on Russia's
overall defense policy, saying "we reject the use of force against
any country as a way to attain a political target."
</P>
<P>
Rodionov and Kyuma agreed to promote bilateral defense dialogue
and cooperation so as to contribute to peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region, Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
The two defense heads also reaffirmed that the first postwar
visit by a Russian Navy ship to Tokyo would take place in late
June, as well as a joint naval drill to prevent naval accidents
and regular bilateral defense meetings at director and vice
ministerial levels.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov conveyed a personal message from President Boris
Yeltsin to Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto in which the Russian
leader underscored the importance of exchange between top defense
and military officials between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kyuma briefed Rodionov on an ongoing review of guidelines on
Japan-U.S. defense cooperation and assured him that Tokyo will
explain the new guidelines to Russia, and to other neighboring
countries such as China and South Korea, when they are drafted,
Kyodo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
