<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Multimedia Corridor Gets Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC) project took another giant step today when
Cyberjaya, its nucleus, was officially launched, marking the start
of the "physical" construction of the MSC.
</P>
<P>
Cyberjaya, Malaysia's first smart city on a 2,800-hectare site,
is located next to Putrajaya, the federal government's new
intelligent administrative capital on a 7,000-hectare site, and is
separated from Putrajaya by a highway to be named Route 2020.
</P>
<P>
The physical development of Cyberjaya will initially involve
3.5 billion ringgit (about 1.4 billion U.S. dollars) and the cost
will be borne by Cyberview Private Limited, which came into being
only days ago to speed up the development of Cyberjaya, according
to officials.
</P>
<P>
Cyberview, a joint venture company between the government's
Multimedia Development Corporation (MDC) and five other partners,
plans to complete the first phase of Cyberjaya's development by
next April. The first phase includes the Multimedia University and
the development of the first 750-hectare Flagship zone, the hub of
the smart city, and the remaining area would be developed in
stages up to the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Seven specific sites have been identified for some of the
pioneering projects in the Flagship Zone.
</P>
<P>
Cyberjaya will have a low density population of 35 persons per
hectare and its target population is 240,000 including 10,000
knowledge workers.
</P>
<P>
Cyberjaya, which is to serve as a regional launch site for
companies developing or using leading multimedia technologies,
will be served by the most advanced physical and software
infrastructure including a 2.5 to 10 gigabit per second broadband
network backbone.
</P>
<P>
The smart city is the core component of the MSC, which also
encompasses the Kuala Lumpur City Center, Kuala Lumpur
International Airport and Putrajaya.
</P>
<P>
The MSC, a 15 kilometer by 50 kilometer zone specially designed
for hi-tech development, is the brainchild of the country's Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad who has been successful so far in
inviting the world's top information and multimedia companies to
invest in the corridor since the launch of the MSC last year.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, major promotional efforts undertaken by Mahathir
himself in the United States and Japan not long ago to explain
personally to potential companies Malaysia's plan to build the
corridor have yielded very good results.
</P>
<P>
His another promotional visit has been planned for next Tuesday
to Europe to meet potential investors there.
</P>
<P>
The MSC continues to receive overwhelming response from
companies with some 900 already having submitted applications to
the MDC for MSC status.
</P>
<P>
A total of 39 companies, both local and foreign, have already
committed to locating their operations in Cyberjaya.
</P>
<P>
Based on the high level of interest generated and positive
feedback received over the past few months, the Malaysian
government is confident that many other companies would soon
follow the lead.
</P>
<P>
MDC Executive Chairman Othman Yeop Abdullah said the qualifying
criteria for MSC status are that the companies must be heavy users
or providers of multimedia/IT products and services with an
intention to transfer technology and employ at least 15 percent
knowledge workers out of the total number of its workforce.
</P>
<P>
Othman said operational conditions to get MSC status include a
separate legal entity for multimedia businesses and activities, a
business location in a designated cybercity and adherence to
environmental guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The successful creation of Malaysia's MSC is expected to have
50 world-class companies at first and 250 companies in the second
stage when the MSC would be linked to nationwide cybercities.
</P>
<P>
The MDC chief said that by the year 2020, the whole country is
projected to be included as an MSC with the participation of at
least 500 world-class IT companies.
</P>
<P>
To protect the investors' interests, a number of cyber laws are
being drawn up with the parliament having already approved the
Computer Crime Bill and the Digital Signature Bill.
</P>
<P>
This mega-sized and international undertaking is creating an
entirely new industry, facilitating Malaysia's transition to an
information-age multimedia economy and making the country more of
a cyber-nation of the world.
</P>
<P>
Officiating the launch of Cyberjaya today, Mahathir also called
on all his countrymen to open up their minds to the wide-ranging
possibilities and opportunities available in Cyberjaya.
</P>
<P>
"Advances in multimedia technology will lead to new
applications, spurring the growth of trade and commerce, as well
as the growth of productivity and efficiency in all the sectors,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
