<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Education Gives Brings Hope to Handicapped Children (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANLING, Guizhou, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen-year-old Li
Enqin is bright: wearing a light yellow coat and taller than all
the other 10 children.
</P>
<P>
Slightly bending her head, Li seems to focus her eyesight
nowhere and keeps playing with the lapels of her coat.
</P>
<P>
The 11 children are all students in Saba Primary School of
Baishui Town, Guanling Buyi and Miao Autonomous County of
southwest China's Guizhou Province. The difference between them
and their classmates lies in that their intelligence quotient (IQ)
is lower than normal people's.
</P>
<P>
An IQ test Li received when she was six years old showed that
her IQ was 48, about half of that a healthy person possesses. Li
was diagnosed as medium obtuse.
</P>
<P>
"Fetch water," said Li quietly when asked what she would like
to do when she grew up. Her answer showed that her teachers'
efforts during the past four years had paid off. Li has changed
her "good-for-nothing" fate by learning some simple labor skills
at school.
</P>
<P>
"Li came to our school in fall, 1991 with nasal drips running
down her nose and tangled hair," recalled Zhang Zhenfu, the head
teacher of Saba Primary School,
</P>
<P>
He added that he and other teachers then did not know how to
teach mentally-retarded children. "It seemed that we teachers were
blind," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and his fellow teachers saw a glimmer of hope three years
ago when a project of "education for children with special needs"
started to be carried out in Guizhou Province. The project was
launched jointly by the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
and the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF and the Guizhou Provincial government had allocated over
456,000 yuan (about 55,000 U.S. dollars) for the project. Baishui
Town and three other towns in the Province project beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF project also brought training opportunities to local
teachers including Zhang Zhenfu. Among teachers who teach blind,
deaf or mentally-retarded children, 239 have received trainings at
various levels. Besides, 142 parents of disabled children also
received training.
</P>
<P>
"I've been to Beijing twice to receive national training in
special education," said Zhang, "I've visited special schools for
mentally-retarded children. What I've learned has been very useful
and helped improved the quality of special education at my
school."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Education Brings Hope to Handicapped Children (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"To Guizhou Province, the project means much more than
statistics can show," said Pi Junlin, chief of the Basic Education
Section of the Guizhou Provincial Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
Pi said that more than 13,000 disabled children were at school
in Guizhou last year, over 7,000 of whom were studying in the same
classroom with normal children. The enrollment rate for disabled
children increased to 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
There were only some 1,000 disabled children at school in 1993
before the UNICEF project was started in the province. The
enrollment rate was almost zero -- 0.05 percent, Pi said.
</P>
<P>
Li Enqin, who is now a student of grade five, can correctly
write her own name and do some simple calculations. She can also
cook rice and fry potato slices for her family. In her spare time,
she can also follows her parents in cutting grass on hillsides
and picking up maize.
</P>
<P>
The progress Li has made meets the goal for China's special
education -- to help disabled children study knowledge and learn
some skills, so that they will be able to become involved in
social life on an equal footing with other children.
</P>
<P>
China began to bring disabled children to the classroom of
normal children on a trial basis in the early 1980s. The
traditional arrangement was to open special schools for disabled
children.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with such arrangements, disabled children could
not experience the life of normal healthy children. It was also
difficult for normal children to show care for and sympathy with
the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Moreover,many localities cannot afford special schools. Parents
usually do not expect much out of their disabled children, and
they do not want to pay a considerable amount of money to send the
disabled to special schools.
</P>
<P>
"Things have changed, so that disabled and normal children are
mixed in the same classroom," said Wang Minyang, deputy chief of
the Special Education Section of the State Education Commission
(SEC). And the mixed education has become a "very important" mode
for China's special education, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mixed education, drawing on foreign experiences while giving
consideration to China's specific conditions, has proved to be
successful in some areas across the country, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that over 320,000 disabled children
nationwide were at school in 1996, 25,500 more than in the
previous year. Almost two thirds of them are studying in ordinary
schools.
</P>
<P>
The SEC re-adjusted its policy by promoting mixed education as
the mainstay of special education in its Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The mixed education, however, has encountered some problems.
Teachers' training and the reform of teaching methods are two
major problems, Wang said. China is seeking effective solutions to
these problems by summarizing experiences.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
