<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Smoking Drive to Be Stepped Up in Transportation Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese authorities in charge of
public health and transportation today urged related departments
to thoroughly implement the regulation banning smoking in public
transportation facilities.
</P>
<P>
The smoking ban covers passenger trains, ships, planes, buses,
subways, taxi cabs, ferry boats, cable cars, and waiting rooms at
railway stations, airports and seaports.
</P>
<P>
The regulation, which has been in effect since May 1, was
jointly promulgated by the ministries of Public Health,
Communications, Railways and Construction, as well as the Civil
Aviation Administration of China and the National Patriotic
Hygiene Campaign Committee (NPHCC).
</P>
<P>
It was the first smoking ban jointly announced by China's
central governmental departments, even though four provinces and
70 cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin, have
formulated local regulations to prohibit smoking in public places.
</P>
<P>
"It is urgent to step up anti-smoking measures, since smoking
and passive smoking have become a serious public health problem in
China, especially in public transportation facilities," said
Minister of Health Chen Minzhang.
</P>
<P>
"To ban smoking from public places also reflects the level of
social civilization and public morality," Chen, also deputy
director of the NPHCC, told a meeting on promoting the implementation
of the regulation here today.
</P>
<P>
Smoking and passive smoking in public transportation facilities
have resulted in an increasing number of complaints from the
Chinese public.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the Ministry of Railways, among
the one billion or so train passengers travelling yearly, about 60
percent are smokers.
</P>
<P>
"Because of limited space inside public transportation
facilities, smoking does more harm not only to smokers but to
those in their vicinity, particularly women and children," Chen
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged related departments to set up full-time organizations
to make regular inspections while seriously punishing violators
of the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the ministries and the CAAC said they are
formulating detailed measures for enforcing the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Publicity activities will also be intensified, the officials
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
