<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Lawmakers Read Societies Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) met in South China's Shenzhen city
today for the first and second readings of a package of bills
including the Societies (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
Michael Suen, secretary for policy co-ordination of the HKSAR
Chief Executive's Office, told the members of the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) that the revised amendment to the bill
was formulated after the office sought opinions from the public in
the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
In early April, the office issued a consultation document to
solicit opinions and suggestions from the communities on its
proposals on the amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the
Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were made by the office in line with a resolution
of the Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress
that major amendments to the two ordinances introduced in 1992 and
1995 shall not be adopted as the laws of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that in the past three weeks, the office received a
total of 5,507 written submissions.
</P>
<P>
He told the PLC that in accordance with article 16 of the
amendment societies bill "a society which has notified the
Societies Officer as required under the Societies (Amendment)
Ordinance before July 1, 1997, is taken to be a registered
society."
</P>
<P>
He mentioned that this ordinance should come into operation on
July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Societies Officer may, after consultation with the
Secretary for Security, refuse to register or to exempt from
registration a society, if he reasonably believes that the refusal
is necessary in the interests of national security or public
safety, public order or the protection of the rights and freedoms
of others, and or if the society is a political body and has a
connection with a foreign political organization or a political
organization of Taiwan, Suen said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bill clearly defines the terms such as
"national security," "political body," "foreign political
organization," "political organizations of Taiwan" and
"connection."
</P>
<P>
Suen pointed out that "national security" is defined in the law
to refer to "the safeguarding of the territorial integrity and
the independence of the People's Republic of China" while
"political organizations" mean political parties or organizations
whose principal functions are to promote and prepare candidates
for elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that the making of these amendments fully represents
the HKSAR government's determination to fulfill its commitment to
safeguard individual rights and freedoms which Hong Kong currently
enjoys and to maintain social stability in the territory.
</P>
<P>
At an earlier press conference in Hong Kong, Suen said that the
bill amendments are also aimed at "guarding against interference
by foreign political forces in local political activities."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLC Members Study Public Order Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The provisional legislature of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) met here today
for the first and second readings of the Public Order (Amendment)
Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
Michael Suen, secretary for policy co-ordination of the HKSAR
Chief Executive's Office, told the members of the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) that the revised amendments to the bill
was formulated on the basis of seeking the opinions from the local
communities in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
In early April, the office issued a consultation document to
solicit opinions and suggestions from the communities on its
proposals on the amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the
Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were made by the office in line with a resolution
of the Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress
that major amendments to the two ordinances introduced in 1992 and
1995 shall not be adopted as the laws of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The office received a total of 5,507 written submissions on the
amendments, Suen said.
</P>
<P>
According to Suen, the Public Order (Amendment) Bill "aims at
striking a proper balance between civil liberties and social
order."
</P>
<P>
He told the PLC that in accordance with article 6 of the bill
"a public procession" may take place if the Commissioner of
Police is notified of the intention to hold the procession and if
the Commissioner of Police is taken to have issued a notice of no
objection.
</P>
<P>
Article 7 of the bill stipulates that the Commissioner of
Police may object to a public procession being held if he
reasonably believes that the objection is necessary in the
interests of national security or public safety, public order or
the protection of the rights and freedoms of others, Suen said.
</P>
<P>
He added that if the Commissioner of Police does not object to
a public procession being held he shall notify the person, who
gave notice, in writing of his having no objection to it within
the time limit under the amendment bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Youth Urged to Prepare for Future SAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese official said here
today that Macao youth should make efforts for a smooth transition
and prepare for the future Macao Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
also urged the youth to take an active part in the transitional
affairs in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering marking the 20th anniversary of the
founding of the Youth Committee of the Macao Chamber of Commerce,
Wang said, "Young people in Macao will experience and witness
China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Macao on
December 20, 1999."
</P>
<P>
"They should take it as their responsibility to promote a
smooth transition and to strive for a better future as they are
also the participants of the historic process," he told some 500
people present on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, he said, the youth should study hard and
improve themselves continuously.
</P>
<P>
"Macao needs thousands of professionals in such fields as
economy, culture, technology, law, education and administration in
the upcoming handover of power and the formation and development
of the Macao Special Administrative Region," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the director said the young people should also
play an active role in promoting the Basic Law of Macao, in major
transitional issues like the localization of the civil service and
law and the use of Chinese as an official language and in
maintaining social stability and economic growth in the territory.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's handover on July 1 this year means a "major
encouragement" and serves as a model for the return of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Wang quoted China's Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen as saying a preparatory committee will be formed early next
year.
</P>
<P>
Kou Hoi In, director of the Youth Committee of the Macao
Chamber of Commerce, pledged that Macao youth will carry on
patriotism, be united and actively participate in Macao's
transitional affairs.
</P>
<P>
"As Hong Kong is returning soon and Macao will return in 945
days," he said, "Macao youth will carry on patriotism and embrace
their historical destiny, meet the challenge of the time and make
greater efforts for the reunification of the motherland and
Macao's smooth handover of power."  
</P>
</TEXT>
