<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Become Big Winners at East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea had the biggest share by
taking 11 out of 32 gold medals at stake while Hong Kong obtained its
first gold medal on Saturday at the second Pusan East Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
However, the host remained in the third overall spot with 34 golds,
next to China with 50 and Japan with 40 as the latters secured six
more gold medals apiece.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan also strode forth with eight more gold medals on the day
by collecting seven out of 12 in the boxing competitions, keeping its
fourth place with 23 gold medals.
</P>
<P>
The host had a clean sweep of four golds in taekwondo, and pocketed
other four from the boxing rings, two from judo and one from the
athletics competitions.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong opened its gold account through Ng Siu-ching who scored
the most of 9.530 points in the women's Nanquan finals.
</P>
<P>
With all Asian marks remain intact on the day, Chinese Huang Geng,
Asian record holder in the men's long jump, failed miserably with his
best jump of 8.03 for the second place, a far cry from his Asian mark
of 8.38 meters set in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"But I still felt satisfied with the jumps today because I was
walking down the slope off my peak," said Huang who leapt to 8.33
meters in the Japanese invitational meets days before the East Asian
Games.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's seven-gold hunting spree in the boxing rings was
initiated by Boulat Djoumadilov in the 51-kg fly weight finals, and
wounded up by Serik Umirbekov in the over 91-kg super heavy category.
</P>
<P>
The other five golds for Kazakhstan were through Bolat Niazymbetov,
Nourjan Smanov, Ermakhan Ibratmov, Yermek Nyssanov and Roustam
Toursenkanov in the 63.5kg, 67kg, 71kg, 75kg and 81kg categories.
</P>
<P>
South Korea got the first boxing title through Choi Jun-wook in the
48-kg light fly category by outbeating Chinese Yang Xiangzhong and had
three more through Choi Seung-rock, Shin Eun-chul and Go Young-sam.
</P>
<P>
Of the 10 athletics gold medals, both China and Japan had an equal
share of four, with the other two split by Kazakhstan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Jiao Baozhong, 27, outpaced Japanese Daisuke Ikeshima in
the last 150 meters to take the day's first event of the men's 20,000
meters walk by clocking in 1:23:58.59.
</P>
<P>
The other three gold medals for China were through its women
athletes while Japan had their national anthem echoed four times
through its men athletes.
</P>
<P>
Yan Jiankui and Chen Yuxiang finished one-two for China by clocking
23.44 and 23.82 respectively in the women's 200 meters, leaving the
bronze medal to Motoka Arai of Japan in 24.09.
</P>
<P>
"I had a medial performance today but I was confident of taking the
gold medal," said the 21-year-old Yan who clocked 22.86 in the
National Champions Competitions last year.
</P>
<P>
Li Lei of China, who suffered the year long injuries to her waist,
threw her winning distance of 56.92 meters in the fifth attempt to
take the javelin title, beating two South Koreans to second and third
spots.
</P>
<P>
Li Lei, eighth-placer in the Atlanta Olympics, said "the injuries
had halted my training time and again in the year, and now I am aiming
for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jian surged ahead from the beginning and quickened her steps
to clock 2:06.16 in the women's 800 meters, beating Japanese Minori
Hayakari to a distant second place in 2:07.65. Chinese Zhang Jinqing
finished third in 2:10.05
</P>
<P>
"I had paced the field from the beginning as I was in a solid
standing to win the event, but I had not fully displayed my powers in
the finals."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese champions were Koji Murofushi in the hammer throw,
Koji Ito in the 200 meters, Masaki Morinaga in the long jump and
Kazuhiko Yamajaki in the 400 meters hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Koji Ito finished in a new games record of 20.98 seconds, Koji
Murofushi took the hammer title in 73.40 meters, Kazuhiko Yamajaki
threw to a distance of 49.60 meters and Masaki Mirinaga jumped to his
winning mark of 8.13 meters.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Soon-hyong took the men's 800 meters in 1:49.00
and Natalya Torshina of Kazakhstan won the the women's 400 meters
hurdles in 55.90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
After three-day athletics competitions, Japan enjoyed a slim edge
over China for the top spot in the gold tally with 11 against 10.
Kazakhstan ranked third with six and South Korea with three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
