<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, US End Naval Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The five-day Egyptian-U.S. "Eagle
Salute" naval exercises ended today in the Red Sea waters
where for the first time the two sides battled each other in
simulation.
</P>
<P>
The drills, which covered an area from northern Hurghada, in
the east of the country facing the Red Sea, to a point south of
Al-Quseir along the Red Sea, were designed to enhance the planning
and management of the joint work of Egyptian-U.S. naval forces,
according to the Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA).
</P>
<P>
The exercises, an annual event since 1992, have witnessed the
participating Egyptian and U.S. air and naval units "fight" each
other as imaginary enemies, instead of training as a joint force.
</P>
<P>
According to the rules of the game, each side was left to rely
on its own resources, waging a mock battle according to a plan
kept secret from the other side.
</P>
<P>
The simulated battle began Monday night, the fifth of the
lunar Muslim month, when the moon was hardly visible. The date
had reportedly been chosen carefully to make it difficult for the
participating forces to spot the "enemy."
</P>
<P>
Admiral Ibrahim Youssef Ibrahim, commander of Egypt's Red Sea
naval base, said the most important feature of this year's
exercise was two frigates (from the two sides) "fought" each other.
</P>
<P>
"The participating forces focused on how to use the nature of
the Red Sea theater of operations to their best advantage. The
Red Sea is the favorite theater of the Egyptian forces who have
learned to enlist its natural features as an added weapon," he
was quoted by local Al-Ahram Weekly.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the "Eagle Salute" naval exercise, the Egyptian
and U.S. ground forces have been staging the biennial "Bright
Star" maneuvers since Egypt signed a peace deal with Israel in
1979.
</P>
<P>
This year's "Bright Star" will be staged in September in the
Western Desert and along the country's northern coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
