<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of Crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week mixed
with the first two lower and the third higher.
</P>
<P>
CPO physicals had bearish performance this week with May South
closing the week 40 ringgit (about 16 U.S. dollars) lower to 1,310
ringgit (about 524 U. S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The market sentiment at present is weak following the bearish
palm oil export data for April 1997 released by the Palm Oil
Registration and Licensing Authority (PORLA) on Thursday. Palm oil
exports in April stood at 570,067 tons, lower from 579,642 tons in
March, against the market expectation that palm oil exports in
April would be within 600,000 to 610,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said CPO physicals are expected to continue their
bearish performance next week on the lack of fresh leads and
buying interest.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), the tin price ended the
week 26 sen lower to 14.17 ringgit (about 5.668 U.S. dollars) per
kg against 14.43 ringgit (about 5.772 U.S. dollars) per kg last
week.
</P>
<P>
Trading was not as active as last week and the market saw a
total turnover slip to 534 tons from 635 tons previously.
</P>
<P>
The price differential between the KLTM and that of the London
Metal Exchange (LME) stood at a premium of 65 U.S. dollars per ton
against 15 U.S. dollars per ton last week.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM is expected to extend its downtrend next week if the
volatile performance of the LME continues, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
However, The Malaysian rubber market saw some light buying of
mostly SMR grades from the Far East, United States, Australia and
Italy this week.
</P>
<P>
The rebound in the Tokyo, Kobe and Singapore rubber futures as
well as other regional markets boosted up the local market's
sentiment, which has been stagnant for quite sometime.
</P>
<P>
June RSS One rose 8.5 sen to close the week at 278.00 sen
(about 111.2 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20 increased by 7.5 sen
to 262.50 sen (about 105 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market price indicator for May 15 was at 214.18 Malaysia/Singapore
cents (sen) per kg against 207.77 cents (sen) on May 8.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 209.45 cents per kg
against 207.91 cents last week.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the local rubber market is expected to extend its
bullishness next week on increased buying interests, especially
from European buyers who normally stock up ahead of the long
summer holidays.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
