<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Sees Big Rise in Measles Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 17 (Xinhua) -- A small outbreak of German
measles has affected more than 1,500 people in Hong Kong so far
this year, a big jump from the 605 cases reported for the whole
year of 1996.
</P>
<P>
An average of 30 patients were hit by the disease every day
last month, according to statistics released by the Hong Kong
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
Patients, most of whom were male and teenagers, would recover
in a few days from the mild symptoms. German measles, known as
rubella, is an infectious disease in which sufferers have small
red spots on the body.
</P>
<P>
Doctors warned pregnant women against contact with sufferers
because the disease may harm their unborn babies.
</P>
<P>
Local medical personnel attributed the sudden rise of victims
to a small outbreak of German measles that occurs every six to
eight years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
