<HEADLINE> Indian PM Favors Debate on Women's Reservation Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral
today favored a national debate on a controversial bill seeking 33
percent reservation for women in parliament and state
legislatures, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The Women's Reservation Bill, presented by Law Minister
Ramakant Khalap in the Lok Sabha (the lower house of parliament)
for consideration on Friday, were strongly opposed by some members
of parliament.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a debate on the issue in the country to decide
about modalities including the percentage to be given to women
under the proposed bill," Gujral said while addressing a meeting
here today.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be debated not only in parliament but in each and
every house countrywide as 50 percent of the populace are involved
in it, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who was prevented from speaking on the
controversial bill in parliament by some members of parliament on
Friday, pointed out that the bill once passed would herald a new
era of social justice in the country.  
</P>
