<HEADLINE> Kazakhstans Take Most Boxing Titles at East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan boxers took seven out of 12
gold medals from the boxing comeptitions which concluded here on
Saturday at the second East Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
But South Korea got the first boxing title through Choi Jun-wook in
the 48-kg light fly category by outbeating Chinese Yang Xiangzhong.
South Korea ranked second with four golds as Japan took home a lonely
gold from the 57-kg feather weight through Ikuo Iida who beat Ruslan
Baitokenov of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Boulat Djoumadilov started Kazakhstan's gold-hunting spree by
taking the 51-kg fly weight after outscoring Shinya Hotta of Japan and
Serik Umirbekov wound up their harvest by taking the last event of
over 91-kg super heavy crown by beating Chinese Jiang Tao.
</P>
<P>
The other five golds for Kazakhstan were through Bolat Niazymbetov,
Nourjan Smanov, Ermakhan Ibratmov, Yermek Nyssanov and Roustam
Toursenkanov in the 63.5kg, 67kg, 71kg, 75kg and 81kg categories.
</P>
<P>
China had only five silvers and six bronzes from the six-day
12-event competitions.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Yang Xiangzhong, the Chinese boxers of Yang Yi, Zhao
Yong, Jiang Tao and Mijit Abuduxikeer all lost their finals to rank
second in the light welter, light heavy, heavy and super heavy
categories respectively.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan ranked first with seven golds, two silvers and three
bronzes, beating the host South Korea to second with four golds, three
silvers and four bronzes. Japan ranked third with one gold, two
silvers and three bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia took other six bronzes with Chinese Taipei had one lonely
bronze medal from the 91-kg heavy category through Lo Shang-che.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
