<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand Vow to Enhance Mutually Beneficial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Thailand today
emphasized the necessity for the two countries to work in
partnership, at bilateral and regional levels, for their mutual
benefit and for the promotion of peace and prosperity in Southeast
Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued here today on the conclusion of
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's two-day official visit
to Myanmar, both sides reiterated the importance they attach to
the further development of good-neighborly relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit reaffirmed Thailand's policy to see the admission of
Myanmar as a member of ASEAN, along with Laos and Cambodia, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers noted with satisfaction the ongoing
bilateral cooperation under the economic and technical assistance
program extended by Thailand, agreeing to explore possibilities
for further cooperation, it said.
</P>
<P>
The two governments hope to sign the agreement on cultural
cooperation by the end of this year to mark the 50th anniversary
of the establishment of diplomatic relations between the two
countries in August 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to utilize to the fullest extent existing
mechanisms and framework for enhancing bilateral cooperation,
having the opinion that regular exchange of visits between senior
naval officials and the establishment of direct channel of
communications between the two forces would contribute to the
maintenance of security at sea, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers agreed to expedite the demarcation of
Myanmar-Thailand boundary, welcoming the signing during Chavalit's
visit of the Agreement on Border Crossing between the Two
Countries and the Exchange of Notes concerning the jurisdiction
over the Thai-Myanmar Friendship Bridge on the Moei/ Thaungyin
River as a significant step forward in facilitating trade,
transport and communication between the two countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also agreed that both sides shall
intensify efforts to improve and expand the network of land, sea,
river, rail and air transport and telecommunication linking the
two countries as well as to expedite negotiations on the
conclusion of the Agreement on Commercial Navigation on Upper
Mekong River, it added.
</P>
<P>
Both sides recognized that each country has the right to pursue
its own path of national development and that outside interference
would be counterproductive, it said.
</P>
<P>
The communique added that Chavalit extended an invitation to
Than Shwe, his Myanmar counterpart, to pay an official visit to
Thailand, which was accepted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
