<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Central Bank Succeeds in Defending Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Speculators in Southeast Asian
currency markets began selling US dollars on Friday, which is a
sign that speculation against the Thai baht had calmed down.
</P>
<P>
In the currency war against the baht which started on Wednesday
and continued on Thursday in overseas markets, the Bank of
Thailand appeared to have regained the upper hand, and
speculators, in particular Americans and Europeans, had lost huge
sums of money in their bets against the baht, dealers and
economists said.
</P>
<P>
The baht traded around 25.80 to the dollar in the spot market
on Friday. In Singapore it moved as high as 25.30 compared with
Thursday's close of 25.50 and Wednesday's 26.33.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night the trading rate of the baht against the
dollar sank to an 11-year low in some western foreign currency
markets.
</P>
<P>
Speculators on Wednesday started the battle by selling baht and
buying dollars. The increase in baht supply pushed the value of
the baht downward, forcing the Bank of Thailand to order all 29
Thai and foreign commercial banks in Thailand to stop selling baht
to foreign speculators, and instructed them to charge the
speculators dearly as a punishment if they wanted to borrow baht.
</P>
<P>
The speculators ended up being charged an overnight two baht
premium on every US dollar, equivalent to an interest rate of
1,000 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, speculators' losses this week had been "fearsome,"
as much as one to 1.25 baht per dollar, a Bangkok-based foreign
trader said.
</P>
<P>
About 20 US and European banks have lost between 100 million
and 200 million dollars each over the past week as a result of
their unsuccessful assault on the baht.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand, which kept the domestic market relatively
unaffected, would not reveal how much it has spent defending the
baht.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the central bank's initial victory, share prices
gained 0.6 percent, or 3.32 points, on Friday, as investors hunted
for bargains with fears of baht devaluation fading.
</P>
<P>
The slight rise in the share price index on Friday came after
plunges over the first four days in the week, totaling 47.56
points, or 7.85 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the battle to defend the baht cannot yet be considered
over.
</P>
<P>
Even though the Thai central bank makes almost daily
announcement to deny a baht devaluation, the baht is not out of
the woods.
</P>
<P>
Speculators who lost so much during the past week would
certainly lie in wait for another opportunity to make assault on
the baht and to force it to devalue.
</P>
<P>
What is more, analysts believe that there are no clear signs of
an economic recovery in the country. Exports remain stalled and
news in the battered finance and property sectors is likely to get
worse before it gets better.
</P>
<P>
All these factors make the baht still vulnerable to
speculation, despite the fact that the central bank could use
probably 10 billion dollars out of its 38 billion dollars in
reserves to save the baht before it had no choice but to devalue
it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
