<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) closed the week lower with the Composite Index
(CI) at 1,041.91 points, 65.46 points lower from 1,107.37 points
at last week's close due to the weakened Thai baht amid fears that
the situation may affect the local currency ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index fell 18.76 points to 297.99 from 316.75 and the
Industrial Index eased 78.63 points to 1,969.05 from 2,047.68 last
week.
</P>
<P>
The Second Board index slipped 30.1 points to 516.07 from
546.17 points previously.
</P>
<P>
The market was mostly bearish throughout the week where the CI
closed at 1,088.52 on Monday and drifted further to close Thursday
at 1,041.27 points, thus recording a 16-month low as a result of
the baht devaluation.
</P>
<P>
However, positive economic figures released on Friday pushed up
share prices to close the week off their lows.
</P>
<P>
The weekly main board turnover increased to 951.776 million
shares worth 5.304 billion ringgit (about 2.1216 billion U.S.
dollars) from 894.463 million shares valued at 5.185 billion
ringgit (about 2.074 billion U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover rose to 142.836 million shares worth
1.448 billion ringgit (about 579.2 million U.S. dollars) from
105.749 million shares valued at 1.227 billion ringgit (about
490.8 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Direct business deals increased to 143.460 million shares worth
1.239 billion ringgit (about 495.6 million U.S. dollars) from
119.285 million shares valued at 918.711 million ringgit (about
367.4844 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the KLSE is likely to open higher next week but
whether it is sustainable over the medium term is still
questionable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
