<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Accepts British Offer of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Gerry Adams, leader of the IRA's
political wing Sinn Fein, today accepted an offer by the British
government for preliminary peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Adams said it had contacted the British government to arrange a
meeting which "should be done without delay," local reports
said. But he did not specify the time and place of the talks.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair offered to send his officials
to meet Sinn Fein party without seeking an IRA truce first. Both
Britain and Ireland banned official contact with Sinn Fein after
IRA quit a 17-month ceasefire in February of last year.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has been fighting against the British rule in Northern
Ireland over the past 28 years, causing heavy loss of lives and
damage of properties.
</P>
<P>
Adams and Sinn Fein's political negotiator, Martin McGuinness,
would go to London on Monday. Both of them have won seats in
British parliament in the May 1 general election.
</P>
<P>
Adams said he would be talking to British officials on the
basis of Sinn Fein's electoral mandate. The party polled some 16
percent of votes in the Catholic Irish nationalist community in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
But the Sinn Fein leader rejected any negotiation of a new IRA
ceasefire. The IRA did not make any terrorist bombs since Labor
government took power early this month, a sign of cooperation with
the new government to break the deadlock on the Northern Ireland
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"I have always refused to engage in any speculation about the
IRA because Sinn Fein is not the IRA and we have neither the
responsibility or authority or ability to negotiate a ceasefire,"
Adams said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Record Holder Fails in Long Jump at East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Asian record holder long jumper Huang
Geng of China failed in his discipline on Saturday as both China and
Japan took four gold medals each from the third-day athletics
competitions at the second East Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Huang, who set the record of 8.38 meters in 1995, leapt to
a miserable distance of 8.03 meters for the silver medal as Japanese
Masaki Morinaga took the men's title in 8.13, while Chen Jing of China
finished third in 7.92 meters.
</P>
<P>
"I was red-flagged in two best attempts of over 8.20 meters, but I
still felt satisfied with the jumps today as I was walking down along
the slope off the peak," said the 27-year-old Huang.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Jiao Baozhong, 27, of Liaoning province, outpaced Japanese
Daisuke Ikeshima in the last 150 meters to take the day's first event
of the men's 20,000 meters walk by clocking in 1:23:58.59. Daisuke
ranked second in 1:23:59.99, with his compatriot Hirofumi Sakai taking
the bronze medal in 1:27:39.38.
</P>
<P>
The other three gold medals for China were through its women
athletes as Yan Jiankui winning the 200 meters, Li Lei in the javelin
and Zhang Jian in the 800 meter finals.
</P>
<P>
Yan Jiankui and Chen Yuxiang finished one-two for China by clocking
23.44 and 23.82 respectively in the women's 200 meters, leaving the
bronze medal to Motoka Arai of Japan in 24.09.
</P>
<P>
"I had a medial performance today but I was confident of taking the
gold medal," said the 21-year-old Yan who clocked 22.86 in the
National Champions Competitions last year.
</P>
<P>
Li Lei who suffered the year long injuries to her waist, threw her
winning distance of 56.92 meters in the fifth attempt to take the
javelin title, beating two South Koreans to second and third spots.
</P>
<P>
Li Lei of Beijing, winner of the Asian Championships in 66.58 and
eighth-placer in the Atlanta Olympics, said "the injuries had halted
my training time and again in the year, and now I am aiming for the
2000 Olympics in Sydney."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jian surged ahead from the beginning and quickened her steps
to clock 2:06.16 in the women's 800 meters, beating Japanese Minori
Hayakari to a distant second place in 2:07.65. Chinese Zhang Jinqing
finished third in 2:10.05
</P>
<P>
"I had paced the field from the beginning as I was in a solid
standing to win the event, but I had not fully displayed my powers in
the finals," said Zhang Jian who had her personal best of 1:59.45.
</P>
<P>
Japan reapt its four gold medals through all men athletes with Koji
Murofushi in the hammer throw, Koji Ito in the 200 meters, Masaki
Morinaga in the long jump and Kazuhiko Yamajaki in the 400 meters
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Koji Ito finished in a new games record of 20.98 seconds, Koji
Murofushi took the hammer title in 73.40 meters, Kazuhiko threw to a
distance of 49.60 meters and Masaki jumped to his winning mark of 8.13
meters.
</P>
<P>
The other two golds of the day were split by South Korean Kim
Soon-hyong in the men's 800 meters and Natalya Torshina of Kazakhstan
in the women's 400 meters hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Korean Kim Soon-hyong and Lee Jae-hoon finished one-two for the
hosts by clocking in 1:49.00 and 1:50.75 respectively and Chinese
Zhang Yi finished third in 1:50.78.
</P>
<P>
Natalya took the last athletics title of the day by finishing in
55.90 seconds in the women's 400 meters hurdles, beating Hsu Pei-chin
of Chinese Taipei to second in 58.00 and Chinese Li Rui to third in
58.06.
</P>
<P>
After three-day athletics competitions, Japan edged China for the
top spot in the gold tally with 11 against 10. Kazakhstan ranked
third with six and South Korea with three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
