<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Indonesia Favorites for Sudriman Cup (Preview) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion China
and 1995 finalist Indonesia are the favorites to win the Sudirman
Cup world mixed team championship starting here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, fresh from their victories at the All-England Open
this March in Birmingham, England, vowed to carry on the winning
momentum to defend their title here.
</P>
<P>
The team, which arrived here two days ago, boasts all the
players who have won four of the five titles at stake at the
All-England Open.
</P>
<P>
China is spearheaded by world number ones in three events:
All-England men's singles champion Dong Jiong, All England and
world women's singles titlist Ye Zhaoying and All England and
Olympic women's doubles champions Ge Fei and Gu Jun.
</P>
<P>
Ge Fei also teamed up with Liu Yong to win the All-England
mixed doubles, making the Chinese overall strength more powerful.
</P>
<P>
The only weakness lies in the men's doubles, where Indonesia's
world number one and three duos Candra Wijaya/Budiarto Sigit and
Denny Kantono/Budi Antonius are dominating.
</P>
<P>
The South East Asian island nation sent here defending men's
singles champion Heryanto Arbi, Olympic women's singles runner-up
Mia Audina, now ranked third in the world in women's singles, and
veteran Susi Susanti.
</P>
<P>
They also have second-ranked women's doubles pair Eliza/Rosiana
Zelin and mixed doubles world number one Trikus Heryanto and
Minarti Timur.
</P>
<P>
But the two powers will not meet in the round-robin group
matches, as China has been placed as the top-seed in Group A of
the top-flight Division 1 with South Korea and England, while
Indonesia is in Group B with Denmark and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
With the South Korean strength sapped by the retirement of
Olympic women's singles champion Bang Soo Hyun and Gil Young Ah,
half of the 1995 women's doubles world champions and also an
Olympic gold medalist in mixed doubles, the Chinese team is
expected to win its two Group A matches.
</P>
<P>
Indonesians could have troubles to beat Group B rival Denmark
since their top men's singles players Arbi and Joko Suprianto are
still haunted by injuries.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, on the other hand, has 1996 Olympic champion Poul-Erik
Hoyer-Larsen, 1997 Taipei Open champion Peter Gade-Christensen,
1997 Japan Open champion Peter Rasmussen and 1997 Korean Open
Thomas Stuer-Lauridsen to choose from playing the men's singles.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, the only European badminton power that could match the
Asians who monopolize the event, hopes to change its fate as the
perennial third-placer in the past four championships.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals of the Division 1, the only division which
has the medal honors, the winner of Group A will meet Group B
runner-up and vice versa. The final is scheduled on May 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
