<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zairean Rebels Entering Capital After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebels are entering the
capital Kinshasa after Zairean Defence Minister and Chief of Army
Staff Gen. Mahele Lieko Bokungu was killed last night.
</P>
<P>
"Our troops are marching in from the aiport. We are singing as
we are going, and people are cheering", reports reaching here
this morning quoted Laurent Kabila, leader of the rebel Alliance
of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Zaire-Congo, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the rebels were very close to the airport about 25 km
from the city.
</P>
<P>
Kabila spoke after Gen. Mahele was killed late Friday night at
camp Tshatshi in the capital, the barracks residence of Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko, who left the city earlier yesterday
for his palace at Gbadolite in northern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Gen. Mahele was killed by the Special
Presidential Division (DSP). "He went to calm the guys down and
then he was shot," an unidentified western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said he went to the camp with regular army units
to bring DSP members under control. Since his appointment last
December, the general had never been in full control of the DSP.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Mahele was killed, armored cars took up positions
around Kinshasa's Intercontinental Hetel, where prominent members
of Mobutu's 32-year administration were staying.
</P>
<P>
The general was reported to meet rebel leader Kabila in the
Zambian capital today to discuss a transition of power.
</P>
<P>
"Gen. Mahele was to meet Kabila this morning in Lusaka to
discuss a handover of power," said a diplomat in Lusaka, who
declined to be named.
</P>
<P>
"It was a deal brokered by the United States," he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the death of Gen. Mahele, rebel leader
Kabila said he had not heard of it, but he added it was "very,
very bad."
</P>
<P>
Confronted with rebels' advance to the capital, Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko left the besieged city yesterday for
his northern stronghold in Gbadolite. A government statement said
the 66-year-old president had relinquished executive powers.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement added Mobutu did not formally resign "as
head of state", as demanded by Kabila and reportedly proposed by a
peace plan worked out by South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu's departure has triggered speculation that he was on
his way to exile. Diplomats said he would go to Morocco before
arriving in France finally.
</P>
<P>
The United States yesterday welcomed Mobutu's departure from
power. "The day of the dictator should be over in Zaire and we
hope that a different day has arrived," U.S. State Department
Spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Many residents in Kinshasa welcomed the news that Mobutu had
gone. But they were anxious about what would happen in the next
couple of days as rebel forces are closing in on the capital.
They are in fear that the rebel advance might trigger not only a
battle, but also an orgy of looting by the fleeging government
troops. enditem

=05170910

=05170918
NNNN
17:18 17:19 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
