<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nepalese Go to Local Polls Amid Tight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Voters in West Nepal today cast
their ballots to elect village and municipal officials amid tight
security as the country started two-phase local elections, the
second of its kind since this Himalayan kingdom adopted a
multi-party democratic system in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the polls were conducted today in 40 western
districts, including over 1,800 villages and 24 municipalities,
with the polls in many remote hilly villages being postponed
indefinitely due to a boycott campaign by an underground
ultra-leftist movement, the Elections Commission here said.
</P>
<P>
Local administrations in the polling areas took special
measures, such as traffic control, to ensure peaceful elections,
while the country's western borders with India were closed from
Friday to prevent possible criminal activities during the
elections.
</P>
<P>
The local polls are being held in two phases mainly due to lack
of adequate security forces in the country which has only some
40,000 police troops, according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
The government has send additional police personnel to West
Nepal to tighten security for the elections and also put army
soldiers on alert in case of uncontrollable incidents, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, the government's special security arrangements seem to
have failed to stop the leftist guerrillas from blocking the
elections at some remote hilly areas.
</P>
<P>
The underground guerrilla group, which launched
anti-establishment armed struggle last year in West Nepal's hilly
areas, has earlier called a boycott to the elections and
successfully disrupted the nomination filing process at many
villages, mostly in Rolpa, Rukum, Jarjarkot and Salyan districts
in mid-west Nepal, a region about 250 km from the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas have reportedly spread death threats scaring
away would-be candidates and carried out explosions to terrify
voters away from voting.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10 people, including election candidates, policemen and
guerrilla members, have been killed since last week when the
guerrillas increased their anti-election insurgency, local press
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission decided one week ago to postpone the
polls in 40 villages of the region until further notices as no
single nomination was filed there.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bamdev Gautum Thursday admitted that
polls at over 60 villages could not be conducted as many
candidates at other villages have withdrawn their candidacy under
the guerrillas' boycott pressure.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the government will seek a political solution
to the security crisis caused by the ultra-leftist insurgents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports of clashes over the elections between
workers of main opposition the Nepali Congress (NC) party and
ruling partner the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) were pouring in as the NC party accused the
government of ignoring CPN-UML workers' illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
The on-going local elections would be actually a popularity
contest between the NC and the CPN-UML, arch rivals in Nepali
politics since the two parties jointly introduced the multi-party
parliamentary system in the country in 1990 amid a popular
movement.
</P>
<P>
The NC gained majority control of the country's over 4,000
local bodies through the last local elections in 1992 when it was
in power but analysts here said it would lose the advantage to the
CPN-UML this time.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML came to power in March as the biggest partner of
the three-party ruling coalition led by Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand, who is from a small party.
</P>
<P>
After the second phase of the polls scheduled for May 26 in
Central and East Nepal, the country will see new leadership at
various local levels including village, municipality and district,
which will significantly affect results of the next general
election expected in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
