<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Faces Criticism over Fiscal Manoeuvres to Save Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 16 (Xinhua) -- German government is facing a storm of
criticism over its plan to revalue the nation's gold reserves to
help plug widening holes in its budget.
</P>
<P>
Bonn was forced to consider emergency fund-raising measures
including revaluing the central bank's gold reserves and selling
part of its 75 percent stake in the country's telecom flag-carrier
Deutsche Telecom as a government commission reported Thursday that
the government's 1997 tax revenues were projected to fall 18
billion German marks (10.65 billion U.S. dollars) short of earlier
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons, Germany's gold reserves are currently
undervalued at about 14 billion marks (8.3 billion dollars). Under
current market value. they should be 57 billion marks (33.7
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists said revaluing the gold reserves would boost the
Bundesbank's profits and consequently generate addictional revenue
for the national accounts.
</P>
<P>
But such a plan has left Germany open to accusations of playing
fiscal trickery, the very criticism that German officials have
unleashed at Italy and France.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, it was Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini who
expressed strong disapproval after the German plan was leaked.
</P>
<P>
"I would be very surprised if the German government were to
have recourse to accounting gimmicks... to meet a revenue
shortfall for 1997....By doing this, Germany could put in jeopardy
the healthy functioning of European Monetary Union," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Bonn's planned fund-raising measures also raised the eyebrows
of many economists in Frankfurt. For them, those measures
represent an unpleasant psychological and risk encouraging other
European countries to make use of technical loopholes.
</P>
<P>
Although economists said under the European Union Maastricht
treaty, profits from the gold revaluation would not directly help
Bonn meet the critical three percent deficit benchmark to qualify
for the planned single European currency, German Finance Ministry
Theo Waigel maintained that such a step would help retire the big
debts run up from the costly German reunification.
</P>
<P>
This will help Germany meet a separate single currency
benchmark, which requires countries to bring their overall
national debts under 60 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
At a special parliamentary debate on budget issues Friday,
Waigel reiterated his optimism about Germany's ability to make the
grade for the single currency, known as the Euro. "We will not go
above the three percent (of GDP) budget limit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl also defended plans to
revalue the central bank's gold reserves and rejected claims that
it could lead to a loss of confidence in Germany's stable monetary
policies.
</P>
<P>
"For my European partners, the most important thing is that
Germany takes part in the Euro with a solid build, because without
Germany the Euro will not work," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
