<HEADLINE> Arafat Writes to Clinton for Help to Solve Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 17 (Xinhua) -- President of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat has written a letter to
U.S. President Bill Clinton asking him to personally step in to
solve the crisis in the peace process, according to the state-run
Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called on the U.S. to play a more active role in its
mediation efforts, while meeting with U.S. Middle East peace
coordinator Dennis Ross in the West Bank city of Nablus on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in the region last week to conduct his shuttle
diplomacy between Israeli and Palestinian leaders in an attempt
to help revive the peace talks that had broken off since
Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement at Har Homa in
East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
But his mediation failed as Israel rejected a call for the
halt of the construction. Arafat called off a scheduled meeting
with him on Thursday night. It was reported that the Palestinians
accused Ross of siding with Israel in evading the sticking point
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his meeting with Arafat, Ross had also met with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai. He had also exchanged views with EU special
envoy to the Middle East peace process, Miguel Angel Moratinos.
</P>
<P>
Before departure for Washington Friday night, Ross insisted
that there is a very clear desire to find a way to promote the
peace march.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Washington, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Friday night met with Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy in what Israeli officials described as a higher-level
discussion of the peace process predicament. But the report did
not say where the talks took place.
</P>
<P>
Albright promised continued U.S. support for Israel and made
it clear that she had no intention to visit the Middle East
until the Israelis and Palestinians make the difficult decisions
to advance the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Levy expressed satisfaction over the meeting and said Ross
will return to the Middle East soon to help resume the
negotiations with the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
