<HEADLINE> Italy Urges for Compromise on Albanian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi said here today that he would put pressure on rival
Albanian parties to compromise on the election issue.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who arrived here this evening on a three-hour flying
visit, made the remarks during the talks with his Austrian
counterpart Viktor Klima.
</P>
<P>
Both Prodi and Klima were worried about the current situation
in Albania and hoped that the Albanian parties could reach
agreement on the controversial election law.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha decreed today the dissolution
of the National Assembly before the end of its mandate and the
holding of new parliamentary elections on June 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, most Albanian parties were threatening to boycott the
coming elections, saying that a new election law, passed earlier
today in the parliament, favors Berisha's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that it would be very difficult for the
international community to provide aid to Albania unless rival
Albanian parties compromise to ensure the fairness and
transparency of the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the forthcoming EU summit to be held in Madrid in
July, both Prodi and Klima agreed to have the employment issue
written down on the revised Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Klima also hoped that Italy could be in the first group to join
the single European Currency, the Euro, and Prodi was confident of
this.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty called for EU members to launch the Euro
by January 1, 1999. But scepticism is growing over whether the
deadline can be met as few members have been able to fulfill the
criteria set by the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The EU commission had put Italy's budget deficit for this year
at 3.2 percent of its gross domestic product, which was 0.2
percent above the ceiling set in the Maastricht Treaty for the
entry of the Euro.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
