<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian President Dissolves Parliament for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Albanian President Sali Berisha
announced this evening to dissolve the National Assembly and hold
fresh parliamentary elections on June 29.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Berisha's press office said, "President
Berisha decreed today the dissolution of the National Assembly
before the end of its mandate and the holding of new parliamentary
elections on Sunday June 29, 1997."
</P>
<P>
However, most Albanian political parties were threatening to
boycott the forthcoming elections, saying that a new draft
election law, passed earlier today in the parliament, favors
Berisha's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party, the second-largest party in Albania, and
many other parties boycotted the vote on the draft law and
strongly required amendment to it.
</P>
<P>
The current Democrat-dominated parliament emerged after a
controversial elections held on May 26, 1996. The Socialists
pulled out of the then polls.
</P>
<P>
Albania was plunged into chaos earlier this year after
thousands of families lost their life savings in fraudulent
pyramid investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
Berisha had no option but reach a compromise with other major
parties in the country. Bashkim Fino, a Socialist, became prime
minister of a nine-party Government of National Reconciliation in
March and early elections were conducted.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation is still complicated and delicated now
mainly due to differences between the Democratic Party and other
parties on the revision of the election law.
</P>
<P>
Franz Vranitzky, the special envoy of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), came to mediate among
the Albanian parties on Thursday but again failed to break the ice.
</P>
<P>
This was the fifth visit by Vranitzky to Albania since February
when the unrest broke out.
</P>
<P>
The European envoy told reporters before leaving Albania that
he was worried about the possible boycott of the forthcoming
elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he warned that the OSCE, the European Union and the
European Committee would reconsider the possibilities of providing
humanitarian, economic and financial aid to Albania and of helping
prepare and monitor the elections unless the Albanian parties
reached a compromise on the revision of the election law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
