<HEADLINE> Heat Ties Game Series 3-3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Miami Heat Friday scored a
95-90 win over the New York Knicks, who was suspension-weakened in
the Game Six for Wednesday's brwal, to force a seventh game in NBA
Eastern Conference semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
Game Seven will be Sunday in Miami with the winner playing the
Chicago Bulls in the East finals.
</P>
<P>
The Heat played without starting power forward P.J. Brown, who
will also miss Game Seven. While the Knicks were without their top
two scorers Patrick Ewing and Allan Houston and reserve point
guard Charlie Ward in Game Six.
</P>
<P>
New York starting forward Larry Johnson and guard John Starks
will miss Game Seven for Wednesday's brwal.
</P>
<P>
Alonzo Mourning led Miami with 28 points and nine
rebounds. Hardaway had 20 points and Majerle finished with 18.
</P>
<P>
Chris Childs led the Knicks with 22 points and Johnson added 20.
</P>
<P>
Despite the absence of Ewing, Houston and Ward, the Knicks led
by as many as 10 points after the first quarter and led 44-40 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
Miami tied the game, 64-64, on a three-point play by Isaac
Austin with 51 seconds left in the third quarter and took the
lead, 68-67, on a dunk by Jamal Mashburn with 9:36 remaining in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
But Johnson converted a three-point play and Charles Oakley hit
a corner jumper to give New York a 72-68 advantage.
</P>
<P>
Hardaway then started the decisive 18-7 run with a
three-pointer with 7:12 left.
</P>
<P>
If the Heat wons in Game seven in Miami on Sunday afternoon it
will become just the sixth team in National Basketball Association
history to successfully come back from a 1-3 deficit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
