<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Army Chiefs Inspect Battlefront </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Minister of Power and
Energy Anurddha Ratwatte, who is also deputy minister of defense,
together with Army Commander Rohan Daluwatte have inspected the
government troops in the North of the country, inquiring about
their welfare and needs, according to a local newspaper report
today.
</P>
<P>
The inspection was made just after the government troops
launched the "Jaya Sikuru" (certain victory) operation on Tuesday
in which over 100 Tamil rebels were reportedly killed or injured
while 27 soldiers dead and 40 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
This operation, conducted with the air force support and ground
troops moving forward, backed by armor and artillery, is aimed at
securing a safe land route from Vavuniya to Kilinochchi.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) were fleeing carrying their wounded following the
heavy onslaught of the troops.
</P>
<P>
They are frantic due to the absence of hospital facilities and
are carrying them into nearby jungles, the report quoted a
military spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war against the
government for a separate Tamil state in the North and east of the
country since 1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
