<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Reiterates Opposition to NATO's Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia reiterated today its
opposition to the eastward expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and asked for reform to the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin's aide Evgeny Shaposhnikov told a press
conference that NATO's eastward expansion is "a big mistake" of
the West, adding, "As Russia is now in an unstable situation, it
could not be ruled out that Russia would wield its 'nuclear club'
when cornered."
</P>
<P>
He said the existence of NATO has hindered the process for the
whole international community entering a more perfect security
system. If Russia and NATO failed to reconcile with each other,
Russia would have to find new allies and the world would probably
be in fresh confrontations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Considering this, he stressed, NATO must reform itself to
become an organization like the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia reached an agreement mapping out their
relations on May 14, which is to be submitted for ruling to the
governments of 16 NATO members and Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Yeltsin already expressed his opposition to the NATO
expansion. In a TV interview on Wednesday, he said, "As we
declared before, we are against the expansion."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States officials said that the agreement,
which is expected to be signed between the heads of NATO members
and President Yeltsin in Paris on May 27, would create a formal
joint cooperation council and give Russia a voice, instead of a
veto, in NATO decision-making on European security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
