<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Security in Indonesia Guaranteed: Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian armed forces (ABRI)
has told the public not to be worried by increasing tension in the
campaign, because the military will protect all citizens from any
disturbances.
</P>
<P>
The head of ABRI 's information center, Brig. Gen. Slamet
Supriadi, said here Friday that "people need not worry because
security is guaranteed and ABRI will work all-out to back up this
guarantee."
</P>
<P>
The three contestants should intensify their security
task-force safeguarding the campaign, as security during the
rallies is the responsibility of each contestant, military sources
here today quoted Supriadi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The United Development Party (PPP), the ruling Golkar and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) have been campaigning since
April 27 for the general election on May 29. The campaign will end
on May 23.
</P>
<P>
He said contestants should refrain from using campaign methods
that could create fear, worries, traffic jams and fatalities.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of his call, Supriadi said that
until Thursday 73 people had already died in 914 violence cases
across the country.
</P>
<P>
In this year's campaign, the country is divided into three
groups of campaign areas where the three parties could do their
campaign activities in turn.
</P>
<P>
According to new election rules, motor parades and marches are
not allowed during the campaign. However, all the three parties
have violated the rules by showing their strength in the streets.
</P>
<P>
About 124 million votes are eligible to take part in the
election for 425 seats in the 500-member parliament. The other 75
seats are allocated for military members, who are appointed by the
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
