<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Calls for Untied Market for CIS Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 16 (Xinhua) -- Kazak First Deputy Prime Minister
Nigmatzhan Isingarin said here on Friday that an urgent task in
the integration of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) is
to set up a united market.
</P>
<P>
Isingarin, also chairman of the Integration Committee of
Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan, said there should be a
united market of commodities, services, labor and capital. CIS
members should also develop a customs union and strengthen the
legal basis of their relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there exist some 300 economic agreements
among the CIS members, but most of them, mere demonstration of
intention of the signatories, are not concrete and operational.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the problem to the lack of agreement on a free
trade system and well-coordinated policy on value-added taxes
among CIS members.
</P>
<P>
Isingarin noted that the opening of the border ports and the
efforts on removing tariffs among the four nations have led to the
doubling of Kazakhstan's trade with Kyrgyzstan and a 40 percent
increase in that with Russia in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
