<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from the Latin American countries over the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian economy showed signs of growth
during the first quarter of 1997. Some of the sectors showing
positive signs are construction, with the building of 15 new first
class hotels; power generation, which rose to one million
kilowatts and exports from the Colon duty free zone reaching 1.38
billion dollars, a 5.1 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile has sold 52,375 new motor vehicles in the
first four months of this year, a 2.65 percent increase over the
same period of 1996, announced the Chilean National Association of
Motor Vehicles Companies.
</P>
<P>
April was the month when most vehicles were sold, with 14,069
units, an 8 percent increase over the 1996's and 2.96 percent up
from the last month.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- United States' direct investments in Argentina
reached 7.982 billion U.S. dollars in 1995, more than tripling
that in 1989.
</P>
<P>
A report from the "Investment Foudation" says that 53 percent
of U.S. direct investments went to the manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's manufactures exports registered a 17.3
percent growth in U.S. dollars in 1996 compared with 1995, the
Uruguay Central Bank announced.
</P>
