<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Refuses to Overrule NBA Suspensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. District Court judge Friday
declined to overrule the player bans given by the NBA after
Wednesday's brawl between Miami and New York.
</P>
<P>
The NBA came down hard on the Knicks and Heat on Thursday,
suspending six players a total of seven games. Five Knicks players
were banned a total of six games.
</P>
<P>
NBA Players Association executive director Billy Hunter went to
court claiming the league acted improperly "in suspending those
players who left the bench to act as peacemakers."
</P>
<P>
Judge Jed S. Rakoff's decision came about two hours before the
Knicks, who lead the best-of-seven second-round series with the
Heat 3-2, were due to host game six.
</P>
<P>
Because teams must field no fewer than nine players for playoff
games, the Knicks will be without starting center Patrick Ewing
and shooting guard Allan Houston, as well as guard Charlie Ward.
</P>
<P>
Ward, Ewing and Houston, along with teammates Larry Johnson and
John Starks, were all banned for one game and fined because of the
incident, in which Heat forward P.J. Brown bodyslammed Ward.
</P>
<P>
Ward was fined 6,000 U.S. dollars for his involvement in the
initial incident, while Ewing, Houston, Johnson and Starks were
fined 2,500 dollars for leaving the bench.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Knicks were fined 20,000 U.S. dollars -- 5,000
dollars for each player who left the bench area. Starks also was
fined 5,000 dollars for making an obscene gesture towards the
crowd at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
"All of our players serve as peacekeepers, and the reason they
came out was to protect one of their own," Knicks president Ernie
Grunfeld said. "It's sad that they have to be suspended."
</P>
<P>
Brown was suspended for two games and fined 10,000 dollars for
his actions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
