<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Fends off Speculators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 17 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
Friday succeeded in taming the speculative attacks on the peso by
raising the over-night interest rates from 14 percent to 21
percent.
</P>
<P>
The startling 7 percentage point increase in the over-night
money rates is the highest since 1995 when the peso was under a
similar attack after the Mexican peso went on a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
After the timely intervention in the market by the central
bank, the peso regained its bearing while foreign funds, which
were reported Thursday to have started pulling out, were lured to
come back into the system.
</P>
<P>
At the end of Friday, the peso appreciated to 26.373 against
the dollar after a slight depreciation in the morning to 26.375
pesos to the dollar from Thursday's close of 26.374 pesos. The
total turnover hit 618 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The peso came under speculative attacks Thursday on fears that
the volatility of the Thai baht would spill over to other Asian
currencies.
</P>
<P>
As a preemptive measures, the central bank raised the interest
rates to keep the peso's strength and lure back funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
