<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Econommy Sees Sound Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- An article in the Beijing weekly
"Outlook" for Monday says that supply in the Chinese market was
slightly bigger than demand and that the country's economy had had
a successful "soft landing" in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, there was a moderate decline
in economic growth, coupled with a decline in demand, with some
enterprises operating under designed capacity of production, while
financial institutions have ample funds.
</P>
<P>
The author of the article, Zhang Liqun, called for closer
monitoring of economic development and warned of a possible
further drop in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The author said that conditions are ripe for economic
improvement for the following reasons:
</P>
<P>
-- Both banks and enterprises have a stronger sense of the
risks involved in investment in new projects. Enterprises are
voluntarily pooling funds to expand production and are sharing
technology in accordance with market needs;
</P>
<P>
-- Savings deposits in China have grown and the use of these
accumulated funds has slowed down;
</P>
<P>
-- There are abundant human and material resources for the
readjustment of the economic structure.
</P>
<P>
The economic restructuring centers on changing the product mix
and production suggests that China's economic development has
entered a new phase. Consumer goods have switched from rapid
growth to smoother growth and to trying to survive by developing
new and high-tech products and by technical innovations. They will
become a driving force in China's national economy, the article
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
