<HEADLINE> Southeast China Spending Heavily On Transportation Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Coastal Fujian Province plans to
raise more than 42 billion yuan (5 billion US dollars) for a
"transportation corridor" linking the provincial capital Fuzhou
with Xiamen City.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to take 15 years and will include
superhighways, railways, pipeline, and telecommunications,
connecting the province's four fastest-developing areas: Fuzhou,
Putian, Quanzhou, and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
"With the improving trade and economic ties with nearby Taiwan
and with Hong Kong and Macao, the demand for transportation is
expected to grow rapidly, meaning a need to improve the transport
conditions," a provincial official commented.
</P>
<P>
For various reasons, coastal parts of Fujian lack adequate
port, rail, and highway facilities, and there are no railways
feeding Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve this situation, a superhighway is being
planned between Fuzhou, Xiamen and Zhangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Funds are being raised to build three port terminals at Fuzhou,
Xiamen and Meizhou, and a pipeline for locally-produced oil is
also in the works. 
</P>
</TEXT>
