<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (87-88) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 17 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (87-88) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What official language will Hong Kong use after
1997? English or Chinese?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Article 9 of the Basic Law stipulates that, in addition
to the Chinese language, English may be used as an official
language by executive authorities, the legislature and the
judiciary of the Hong Kong SAR. English is also the official
language in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and English will remain as official languages in the
Hong Kong SAR after 1997, with equal importance given to both
languages. This conforms with Hong Kong's status as an
international economic city.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will Marxist-Leninist studies be introduced to Hong
Kong schools after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Hong Kong has a Western-style educational
system. According tothe Basic Law, the government of the Hong Kong
SAR will, on the basis of the region's existing educational
system, formulate policies regarding the development and
improvement of education there.
</P>
<P>
This approach represents the spirit of leaving Hong Kong's
existing systems basically unchanged as stated in the Sino-British
Joint Declaration as well as opinions of educational circles in
Hong Kong calling for policy flexibility in the field of education.
</P>
<P>
As to whether or not Marxist-Leninist courses will be
introduced to Hong Kong schools after 1997, the question itself
shows a lack of understanding on the part of those who pose the
question about the policy of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
The concept of two systems covers ideological systems as well
as the economic sector. The Basic Law specifically provides that
educational institutions of all types may all retain their
autonomy and shall enjoy academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
They will be permitted to continue recruiting staff and using
teaching materials from outside the Hong Kong SAR, for example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kasparov Wants to Play Deep Blue again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- World chess champion Garry
Kasparov said on Friday he wanted to play the Deep Blue again
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
"I want a to play a longer match of 10 games with better
conditions for a human player," the Russian grandmaster, who just
days after a stunning defeat by the IBM supercomputer, was quoted
by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov said he was prepared to play the match in September or
October in New York but under different conditions from the
six-game contest that ended painfully and bitterly for him on
Sunday and gloriously for a team of computer scientists.
</P>
<P>
Before, during and after the 1.1 million U.S. dollars match,
Kasparov complained that the conditions were essentially unfair
because he had no access to the computer program's practice games
in the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
In Friday's interview conducted by Reuters, he acknowledged
that he had agreed to those conditions but said he also felt
unexpected hostility toward him from Deep Blue team members during
the match.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the company said it was difficult to respond
to Kasparov's comments
</P>
<P>
Women's world champion Susan Polgar has also issued a challenge
to play Deep Blue, an IBM RS/6000 SP parallel processor with
specialised microchips for chess that can examine hundreds of
millions of moves per second.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
