<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North-South Gap in Communications Must Be Closed: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The gap in communications
technology between countries of the North and South should be
closed, representatives of developing countries told a UN meeting
here.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jieyi, representative of China, said this morning that
despite advances, the gap between the developed and developing
countries was growing and developing countries were again facing
the prospect of being marginalized. The control of the mass media
by interests in the developed countries threatened the cultural
and ethical independence of developing countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The mass media would act to promote mutual understanding
between people, world peace and development, Liu said. However,
there had been an unhealthy tendency to use the mass media to
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries, attempting
to impose particular values on other peoples, in total disregard
of the rules of international behavior and basic journalistic
ethics, he said.
</P>
<P>
Antonius Agus Sriyono of Indonesia Thursday urged the United
Nations to promote a more just information and communication order
as media should enhance understanding between peoples, not
perpetuate divisivesness.
</P>
<P>
Jeryong Hong of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
stressed that distorted information on the realities in developing
countries was disseminated in the mass media and misused for the
political purpose of individual countries.
</P>
<P>
Tariq Ali Bakhit of the Sudan said that his government rejected
the disinformation campaigns against it which used such items as
ethnic and religious struggles. The Sudan was alarmed and deeply
regretted the disinformation campaigns aimed at spreading an
incorrect picture of Islam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
