<HEADLINE> UNDP Chief Nominated for Further Four-Year Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 16 (Xinhua) -- James Gustave Speth was
nominated by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan today for another
four years as chief of the United Nations Development Program, the
largest U.N. specialized agency.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in a letter, asked the General Assembly to confirm the
nomination of Speth for a second term beginning on July 16. The
General Assembly will confirm the nomination next Tuesday,
according to the office of the spokesman for the
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Speth was originally proposed for the position by President
Bill Clinton in 1993, and was the senior environmental official in
former President Jimmy Carter's White House.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP distributed close to 1 billion dollars a year to
developing countries to combat poverty and give technical
assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
