<HEADLINE> US Dollar Steadies Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended mostly lower
here today but steadied against the yen somehow, helped by rumors
of central bank sales of the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar finished at 115.55 yen, down from
116.10 Thursday but up from its intraday low of 114.85 yen. The
dollar cost 1.6925 marks, down from 1.6988.
</P>
<P>
The pound weakened broadly. In New York, the pound cost 1.6367
U.S. dollars, down from 1.6426 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar got a temporary boost from a Commerce Department
report of surprisingly strong housing construction in April, which
refreshed speculation that the Federal Reserve will raise interest
rates next Tuesday. Higher rates will make dollar more attractive.
</P>
<P>
Since hitting a 4.5-year high of 127.46 yen on May 1, the
dollar has dropped about 11 yen or nearly 9 percent, erasing its
gains for the year against the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday:
1.4208 Swiss francs, down from 1.4310; 5.6995 French francs, down
from 5.7110; 1,669.25 Italian lire, down from 1,672.00; 1.3735
Canadian dollars, up from 1.3724. 
</P>
</TEXT>
