<HEADLINE> US Offers to Help Zaire in Peaceful Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it would provide assistance for a peaceful transition in
Zaire as President Mobutu Sese Seko had declared cessation of his
32-year rule of the country.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said the United
States would be willing to offer financial and other assistance
to support the transition leading to a "free and fair election."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Bill Clinton said the United States would
"do what we can" to promote a "democratic transition in one of
the largest and most important nations in Africa."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the United States was prepared to offer
about 10 million dollars to support the transition in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
They also said a "democratic Zaire" could receive relief for
the country's U.S. debt, development assistance and
professionalization of the military.
</P>
<P>
But they said Mobutu's prospective successor, Laurent Kabila,
could expect no help from the United States if he opted for what
they called the "Mobutu-style strong-man rule."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters U.S.
officials had discussed the possibility of a "democratic
transition" with Kabila, but had received no commitments from
him.
</P>
<P>
"One way or another, Zaire is about to enter into a new stage
of its history," he said. "It should be a peaceful one and we
believe should be a democratic one and we have encouraged Mr
kabila to recognize the importance of both."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said earlier that the
departure of Mobutu "opens the way for a peaceful resolution of
the military conflict."
</P>
<P>
"I think the most important point here is that Zaire now needs
to move forward away from war towards peace, stability and
elections," she said.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu flew off to Gbadolite, north of the capital of Kinshasa,
today for what his spokesman called a "short rest."
</P>
<P>
Hours later, Information Minister Kin-Kiey Mulumba announced
that Mobutu had "ceased all intervention in the conduct of affairs
of state."
</P>
<P>
"He reigns but does not govern," the information minister told
a press conference. He said Mobutu retained a title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
