<DOCNO> XIE19970517.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 16 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
plunged nearly 140 points today under the pressure from some
surprisingly strong economic data.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, which on Thursday closed above 7,300 for the first
time, lost 138.88 points, or 1.9 percent, to 7,194.67, trimming
the week's gain to 25.14 points.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 485.78
million shares as against 457.18 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market measures also pulled back sharply from
Thursday's record-setting advance.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 12.13 points to
829.75, and the NYSE composite index fell 5.21 to 432.44. Both
measures had closed at record highs on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 12.84 points to 1,340.74, and
the American Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.25 to 586.72.
</P>
<P>
The technology sector was weighed down by a disappointing
profit report from Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
Stocks were pressured from the open by the bond market, which
was weighed down by two reports revealing surprisingly strong
consumer sentiment and housing construction.
</P>
<P>
The policy-makers of the Federal Reserve are scheduled to meet
again on Tuesday to decide whether to raise interest rates or not.
</P>
<P>
As bonds fell today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
rose as high as 6.91 percent from late Thursday's 6.86 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
